1
00:00:37,409 --> 00:00:41,256
[SPEAKER_05]: Welcome to Cameron and Miliband live, the battle for number 10.

2
00:00:41,917 --> 00:00:42,378
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening.

3
00:00:42,799 --> 00:00:49,431
[SPEAKER_05]: Tonight sees the first big election test for two men, one of whom will be the UK's next prime minister.

4
00:00:50,032 --> 00:00:56,424
[SPEAKER_05]: David Cameron and Ed Miliband are the only people with a genuine chance of forming the next government.

5
00:00:56,444 --> 00:00:58,708
[SPEAKER_05]: Tonight, we'll see what they're made of.

6
00:01:00,038 --> 00:01:09,049
[SPEAKER_10]: Over the next 90 minutes, both men will face Jeremy head-to-head, and they'll also answer the questions of our studio audience.

7
00:01:09,069 --> 00:01:16,297
[SPEAKER_10]: Running quickly through the order of play, David Cameron will be interviewed by Jeremy, then join me to take questions from our audience.

8
00:01:16,518 --> 00:01:22,705
[SPEAKER_10]: After that, Ed Miliband will face questions from the studio, and we finish with his head-to-head with Jeremy.

9
00:01:22,685 --> 00:01:23,886
[SPEAKER_10]: So, let's get to it.

10
00:01:23,906 --> 00:01:25,088
[SPEAKER_10]: The election starts here.

11
00:01:25,828 --> 00:01:31,334
[SPEAKER_10]: And now, first up, the Prime Minister and leader of the Conservative Party, David Cameron.

12
00:01:43,847 --> 00:01:48,372
[SPEAKER_05]: David Cameron, do you know how many food banks there were in this country when you came to power?

13
00:01:48,571 --> 00:01:58,186
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't have the exact figures but I know that usage of food banks has gone up and there are many amazing volunteers who man those food banks and provide an important service.

14
00:01:58,207 --> 00:02:01,372
[SPEAKER_05]: There were 66 when you came to power, there are now 421.

15
00:02:01,392 --> 00:02:09,685
[SPEAKER_05]: 900,000 people took food parcels last year, free food parcels.

16
00:02:10,947 --> 00:02:13,391
[SPEAKER_05]: You talked about broken Britain and fixing it.

17
00:02:13,871 --> 00:02:14,312
[SPEAKER_05]: You haven't.

18
00:02:14,372 --> 00:02:15,874
[SPEAKER_05]: It's more broken now than it was.

19
00:02:16,034 --> 00:02:17,356
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I don't accept that.

20
00:02:17,376 --> 00:02:24,627
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if you look at what's happened with our economy, there are 1.89 million more people in work than when I became prime minister.

21
00:02:24,667 --> 00:02:27,571
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got 900,000 fewer people on out-of-work benefits.

22
00:02:27,591 --> 00:02:28,973
[SPEAKER_04]: Is there an increase in food banks?

23
00:02:28,953 --> 00:02:29,934
[SPEAKER_04]: a mark of success?

24
00:02:30,035 --> 00:02:32,899
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, obviously there has been an increase in food bank use.

25
00:02:32,959 --> 00:02:36,544
[SPEAKER_04]: That's partly because of the difficulties we faced as a country.

26
00:02:36,785 --> 00:02:39,509
[SPEAKER_04]: It's also, Jeremy, because we changed the rules.

27
00:02:39,589 --> 00:02:44,836
[SPEAKER_04]: The previous government didn't allow job centres to advertise the existence of food banks.

28
00:02:44,856 --> 00:02:46,379
[SPEAKER_04]: They thought it would be bad PR.

29
00:02:46,679 --> 00:02:47,961
[SPEAKER_04]: I thought that was a wrong decision.

30
00:02:48,061 --> 00:02:49,203
[SPEAKER_04]: I thought it was a poor decision.

31
00:02:49,523 --> 00:02:53,109
[SPEAKER_04]: So we allowed them to point people towards food banks if they needed them.

32
00:02:53,129 --> 00:02:57,475
[SPEAKER_04]: But look, the big picture is here, is we want to get more people back to work.

33
00:02:57,455 --> 00:03:01,359
[SPEAKER_04]: We've turned the economy around, and it's jobs that are the best route out of poverty.

34
00:03:01,379 --> 00:03:08,345
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it acceptable in a rich country like ours that there are that number of people depending on free food aid?

35
00:03:08,625 --> 00:03:14,771
[SPEAKER_04]: Obviously, I want fewer people to be using food banks, and I want more people to have the security of a job.

36
00:03:15,171 --> 00:03:19,295
[SPEAKER_04]: But we have created 1,000 jobs for every day this government's been in office.

37
00:03:19,355 --> 00:03:20,756
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, that's a statistic.

38
00:03:20,776 --> 00:03:27,462
[SPEAKER_04]: But behind that statistic are people who are able to provide for their families, who are earning a wage, who are able to build a better

39
00:03:27,442 --> 00:03:30,739
[SPEAKER_04]: How many of those jobs are zero-hours contracts?

40
00:03:30,759 --> 00:03:34,397
[SPEAKER_04]: About one in 50 jobs are zero-hours contracts.

41
00:03:35,322 --> 00:03:37,706
[SPEAKER_04]: Could you live on a zero-hours contract?

42
00:03:38,246 --> 00:03:38,847
[SPEAKER_04]: No.

43
00:03:39,689 --> 00:03:44,676
[SPEAKER_04]: Some people choose a zero-hours contract, for instance, students, because they want the flexibility.

44
00:03:44,696 --> 00:03:45,518
[SPEAKER_04]: But what we did is...

45
00:03:45,818 --> 00:03:46,439
[SPEAKER_04]: Hold on a second.

46
00:03:46,860 --> 00:03:54,291
[SPEAKER_04]: We outlawed, first government to do this, the idea of exclusive zero-hours contracts where you can only work for one business.

47
00:03:54,311 --> 00:03:56,414
[SPEAKER_04]: So we passed a law saying that shouldn't happen.

48
00:03:56,775 --> 00:03:57,756
[SPEAKER_04]: But it is a myth.

49
00:03:57,916 --> 00:04:01,862
[SPEAKER_04]: Some people want to say the jobs that have been created are all low-paid jobs.

50
00:04:01,922 --> 00:04:02,804
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not true.

51
00:04:02,884 --> 00:04:03,845
[SPEAKER_04]: No-one's saying that.

52
00:04:03,865 --> 00:04:04,266
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm not saying that.

53
00:04:04,246 --> 00:04:06,170
[SPEAKER_04]: The hint you're trying to give is that...

54
00:04:06,651 --> 00:04:10,840
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm saying there are 700,000 people on zero-hours contracts.

55
00:04:11,161 --> 00:04:12,784
[SPEAKER_05]: Could you live on one?

56
00:04:12,844 --> 00:04:16,192
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, as I said, some people... Could you live on one?

57
00:04:16,212 --> 00:04:21,784
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to create a country where more people have the opportunity of the full-time work that they want.

58
00:04:22,044 --> 00:04:23,908
[SPEAKER_04]: Could you live on a zero-hours contract?

59
00:04:23,888 --> 00:04:25,790
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, that's not the question.

60
00:04:25,851 --> 00:04:28,234
[SPEAKER_04]: The question is... Well, it's the question I'm asking.

61
00:04:29,015 --> 00:04:31,418
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, but the point is, some people choose a zero-hours contract.

62
00:04:31,438 --> 00:04:37,385
[SPEAKER_04]: If you're a student, for instance, and you want to do some part-time work, a zero-hours contract can work for you.

63
00:04:37,706 --> 00:04:39,648
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why we haven't outlawed them altogether.

64
00:04:39,688 --> 00:04:42,792
[SPEAKER_04]: What we've outlawed is exclusive zero-hours contracts.

65
00:04:42,832 --> 00:04:45,716
[SPEAKER_04]: And no, I couldn't live on one of those, and that's why we outlawed them.

66
00:04:45,736 --> 00:04:51,263
[SPEAKER_05]: But the person... For example, a colleague of mine this morning spoke to a man in the North East, Patrick.

67
00:04:51,243 --> 00:04:54,848
[SPEAKER_05]: he walks four hours to and from work.

68
00:04:54,888 --> 00:05:02,259
[SPEAKER_05]: When he gets there, he doesn't know whether he's on for one hour or two hours, or if he's lucky, longer, and then he has to walk home again.

69
00:05:02,699 --> 00:05:04,702
[SPEAKER_05]: He gets £6.75 an hour.

70
00:05:05,083 --> 00:05:08,328
[SPEAKER_05]: He works between eight and 12 hours a week on average.

71
00:05:08,908 --> 00:05:11,412
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, is that any way to live?

72
00:05:11,392 --> 00:05:17,985
[SPEAKER_04]: I want more people to have full-time work and that is what is happening in our economy.

73
00:05:18,527 --> 00:05:19,468
[SPEAKER_04]: It has been difficult.

74
00:05:19,789 --> 00:05:26,122
[SPEAKER_04]: We have had a very difficult few years following the longest and deepest recession virtually in our country's history.

75
00:05:26,382 --> 00:05:27,645
[SPEAKER_04]: We are coming out of that

76
00:05:27,625 --> 00:05:30,632
[SPEAKER_04]: We created 1.89 million new jobs.

77
00:05:30,652 --> 00:05:31,895
[SPEAKER_04]: That's 1,000 a day.

78
00:05:32,236 --> 00:05:35,745
[SPEAKER_04]: The majority of those have been full-time jobs, not part-time jobs.

79
00:05:36,186 --> 00:05:39,494
[SPEAKER_04]: Most of them have been in relatively well-paid occupations.

80
00:05:39,955 --> 00:05:44,065
[SPEAKER_04]: Only one in 50 jobs is a zero-hours contract, and some people

81
00:05:44,045 --> 00:05:45,066
[SPEAKER_04]: choose those contracts.

82
00:05:45,086 --> 00:05:50,470
[SPEAKER_04]: But if you ask me, do I want more people to have the dignity and security of work and a regular wage?

83
00:05:50,631 --> 00:05:50,931
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

84
00:05:51,191 --> 00:05:52,692
[SPEAKER_04]: Do I want a higher minimum wage?

85
00:05:53,053 --> 00:05:53,353
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

86
00:05:53,493 --> 00:05:58,797
[SPEAKER_04]: And we've seen the minimum wage increase now above inflation for the first time in many years.

87
00:05:59,178 --> 00:06:02,861
[SPEAKER_04]: And I want to see that minimum wage go through £7 on to £8.

88
00:06:03,081 --> 00:06:07,965
[SPEAKER_04]: And crucially, Jeremy, in terms of what the government can do, we have cut taxes.

89
00:06:08,025 --> 00:06:13,950
[SPEAKER_04]: So we've taken the 3 million lowest paid people in our country out of income tax altogether.

90
00:06:13,930 --> 00:06:18,414
[SPEAKER_04]: so you can earn now £10,600 before you start paying income tax at all.

91
00:06:18,755 --> 00:06:21,377
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that is vitally important, and that's been the priority for the government.

92
00:06:21,397 --> 00:06:23,859
[SPEAKER_05]: But to be clear about this, you couldn't live on a zero-hours contract.

93
00:06:23,879 --> 00:06:27,643
[SPEAKER_05]: This is one of the things people really find problematic about you.

94
00:06:27,683 --> 00:06:29,805
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm going to be personal, if I may, for a second.

95
00:06:30,185 --> 00:06:30,345
[SPEAKER_05]: You can.

96
00:06:30,365 --> 00:06:40,495
[SPEAKER_05]: It is that you would choose, for example, to appoint a man who oversaw tax avoidance as a minister in your government, another rich person.

97
00:06:41,099 --> 00:06:53,404
[SPEAKER_05]: that you would choose to appoint to the heart of government a rich newspaper editor whose newspaper hacked people's phones, that you choose to defend a rich television presenter who thumps a colleague.

98
00:06:53,905 --> 00:06:56,931
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, what do you have in common with all these very rich people?

99
00:06:56,911 --> 00:07:02,217
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's take these in turn, because I think that is completely unjustified.

100
00:07:02,257 --> 00:07:05,440
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's take Stephen Green, who was head of HSBC.

101
00:07:05,841 --> 00:07:10,686
[SPEAKER_04]: He had been appointed by my predecessor, Gordon Brown, to run his business advisory council.

102
00:07:11,087 --> 00:07:20,337
[SPEAKER_04]: I appointed him as a trade minister in a move that was welcomed across the political spectrum, across British industry, as someone who had run a bank responsibly.

103
00:07:20,317 --> 00:07:24,644
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know whether there was wrongdoing subsequently at HSBC.

104
00:07:24,664 --> 00:07:25,205
[SPEAKER_04]: We'll have to see.

105
00:07:25,225 --> 00:07:27,529
[SPEAKER_04]: But nobody criticised that appointment at the time.

106
00:07:27,549 --> 00:07:28,230
[SPEAKER_04]: Did you ask him about it?

107
00:07:28,831 --> 00:07:36,383
[SPEAKER_04]: I didn't ask him about that specific question, but we went through all the normal processes and procedures that you would with appointing a minister.

108
00:07:36,704 --> 00:07:40,570
[SPEAKER_04]: Proper checks, including checks by the Inland Revenue into someone's

109
00:07:40,550 --> 00:07:43,414
[SPEAKER_04]: tax affairs, and so it was properly dealt with.

110
00:07:43,815 --> 00:07:50,825
[SPEAKER_04]: If you want to raise the issue of Jeremy Clarkson, I said very clearly I didn't know what had happened, and so I wasn't going to comment extensively.

111
00:07:50,885 --> 00:07:56,854
[SPEAKER_04]: I just simply answered a question I was asked, explaining he was a friend of mine, he's a talent, and I hope it could be resolved.

112
00:07:57,155 --> 00:08:01,721
[SPEAKER_04]: But I'm absolutely clear, look, treating the people you work with badly is not acceptable.

113
00:08:02,002 --> 00:08:05,507
[SPEAKER_04]: The BBC have made their decision, and that's absolutely right for them.

114
00:08:05,567 --> 00:08:08,852
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think the aspersion you're trying to cast

115
00:08:08,832 --> 00:08:10,433
[SPEAKER_04]: I think he's completely ridiculous.

116
00:08:10,453 --> 00:08:18,761
[SPEAKER_04]: What I have done for the last five years is lead a government that has got the economy growing, has got people back to work, has cut the taxes of the poorest people in our country.

117
00:08:19,121 --> 00:08:23,785
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm not saying we've achieved everything we've set out to do, but the country is immeasurably stronger.

118
00:08:23,825 --> 00:08:25,687
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's come to the question of the economy, then.

119
00:08:25,827 --> 00:08:31,572
[SPEAKER_05]: Apart from broken Britain, one of your slogans last time was that the country was overwhelmed in debt.

120
00:08:31,833 --> 00:08:33,494
[SPEAKER_05]: Overwhelmed was the word you used.

121
00:08:34,855 --> 00:08:36,797
[SPEAKER_05]: How much money have you borrowed?

122
00:08:36,997 --> 00:08:40,343
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we have cut the budget deficit in half as a share of GDP.

123
00:08:40,383 --> 00:08:41,586
[SPEAKER_04]: How much money have you borrowed?

124
00:08:42,888 --> 00:08:46,916
[SPEAKER_04]: The key thing is the amount of money you borrow every year, the deficit... Do you know what it is?

125
00:08:46,936 --> 00:08:47,837
[SPEAKER_04]: ..that is down in half.

126
00:08:47,877 --> 00:08:52,366
[SPEAKER_04]: I know that we have borrowed a lot of money because the deficit adds to your debt every year.

127
00:08:52,386 --> 00:08:53,488
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you know what the figure is?

128
00:08:53,648 --> 00:08:54,931
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, you're going to tell me, Jeremy.

129
00:08:54,951 --> 00:08:55,171
[SPEAKER_04]: I am.

130
00:08:55,672 --> 00:08:59,359
[SPEAKER_04]: It's a mere £500 billion.

131
00:08:59,339 --> 00:09:03,150
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, that is a lot less than the previous government was borrowing.

132
00:09:03,270 --> 00:09:06,359
[SPEAKER_04]: No, it's more than the previous government borrowed.

133
00:09:06,379 --> 00:09:14,361
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, the annual overdraft, the deficit, has come down by one half as a share of GDP and debt, the total stock

134
00:09:14,341 --> 00:09:17,724
[SPEAKER_04]: The debt as a share of our national income is now falling.

135
00:09:17,964 --> 00:09:19,226
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, we haven't finished the job.

136
00:09:19,286 --> 00:09:32,038
[SPEAKER_04]: We have been working to a plan, and the British people have been working incredibly hard to that plan of turning the economy around, getting the deficit down, having public services that we can afford, and creating jobs and livelihoods for all our people.

137
00:09:32,118 --> 00:09:33,519
[SPEAKER_04]: That is what we have been doing.

138
00:09:33,819 --> 00:09:42,087
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, if you're saying we haven't gone fast enough to cut the deficit, I would agree we need to complete the job, but all my political opponents

139
00:09:42,067 --> 00:09:45,995
[SPEAKER_04]: have been saying we should borrow more, we should spend more, we should tax more.

140
00:09:46,395 --> 00:09:49,682
[SPEAKER_04]: That's the alternative that you face with Ed Miliband and his approach.

141
00:09:49,702 --> 00:09:53,770
[SPEAKER_05]: My point is merely the chasm between what was said and what was actually done.

142
00:09:53,810 --> 00:09:54,631
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's take another one.

143
00:09:54,651 --> 00:09:55,573
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's take immigration.

144
00:09:56,275 --> 00:10:02,026
[SPEAKER_05]: You promised at the last election that you would reduce immigration to the level it was at in the early 1990s.

145
00:10:02,286 --> 00:10:04,210
[SPEAKER_05]: Tens of thousands a year.

146
00:10:04,190 --> 00:10:06,193
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you know how many people you actually let in?

147
00:10:06,213 --> 00:10:06,794
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

148
00:10:06,814 --> 00:10:09,098
[SPEAKER_04]: Immigration has not been cut to the tens of thousands.

149
00:10:09,258 --> 00:10:09,659
[SPEAKER_04]: No, it hasn't.

150
00:10:09,679 --> 00:10:10,220
[SPEAKER_04]: You failed.

151
00:10:10,440 --> 00:10:14,307
[SPEAKER_04]: What we did is we cut immigration from outside the European Union.

152
00:10:14,387 --> 00:10:16,069
[SPEAKER_04]: That is down by 13%.

153
00:10:16,170 --> 00:10:21,979
[SPEAKER_04]: We closed down about 800 bogus education colleges, which were really visa factories.

154
00:10:21,959 --> 00:10:25,763
[SPEAKER_04]: But inside the European Union, immigration has increased.

155
00:10:25,783 --> 00:10:32,211
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm afraid not least because we've actually created more jobs in Britain than the rest of the European Union put together.

156
00:10:32,291 --> 00:10:36,195
[SPEAKER_04]: The European Union's economy has been so stagnant that people have come here to work.

157
00:10:36,516 --> 00:10:41,742
[SPEAKER_04]: So what we need to do now is keep the economy working, but fix the broken welfare system.

158
00:10:41,762 --> 00:10:44,084
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm going to just make this point, if you'll let me.

159
00:10:44,365 --> 00:10:51,713
[SPEAKER_04]: There are some key changes I'm going to make, which is that if you come from Europe to Britain, you cannot claim unemployment benefit.

160
00:10:51,693 --> 00:10:55,519
[SPEAKER_04]: If you don't have a job in six months, you'll have to return to the country you came from.

161
00:10:55,819 --> 00:11:02,189
[SPEAKER_04]: You'll have to work here for four years paying into the system before you get tax credits or benefits out of the system.

162
00:11:02,209 --> 00:11:07,918
[SPEAKER_04]: And while you're here, you can't send child benefit home to the family if they're living in another country.

163
00:11:07,978 --> 00:11:12,705
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, those changes taken together, key welfare changes, will reduce

164
00:11:12,685 --> 00:11:15,149
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not what you said last time.

165
00:11:15,249 --> 00:11:16,471
[SPEAKER_05]: It's not what you said last time.

166
00:11:16,711 --> 00:11:25,625
[SPEAKER_05]: You said, quote, no ifs, no buts, we make a promise to the British people that we will reduce immigration to the level it was at in the early 1990s.

167
00:11:25,925 --> 00:11:27,167
[SPEAKER_05]: You've not done it.

168
00:11:27,267 --> 00:11:32,235
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I believe that is still the right ambition, and we achieved a cut from outside the EU, but inside the EU...

169
00:11:32,255 --> 00:11:34,158
[SPEAKER_04]: It was a no ifs, no buts promise, not an ambition.

170
00:11:34,178 --> 00:11:39,486
[SPEAKER_04]: Inside the EU, we haven't achieved it, but we need to make these welfare changes in order to do it.

171
00:11:40,867 --> 00:11:43,640
[SPEAKER_05]: But you accept you haven't met the promise there?

172
00:11:43,660 --> 00:11:45,609
[SPEAKER_04]: We've not met the commitment that I made.

173
00:11:45,709 --> 00:11:46,553
[SPEAKER_04]: I fully accept that.

174
00:11:46,975 --> 00:11:47,417
[SPEAKER_05]: Right.

175
00:11:48,595 --> 00:11:50,638
[SPEAKER_05]: There's a whole credibility problem here, isn't there?

176
00:11:50,658 --> 00:11:57,609
[SPEAKER_05]: Because one of the other things you said, and you repeated it again this week, yesterday, I think, you said, we're not going to raise VAT.

177
00:11:57,889 --> 00:12:01,054
[SPEAKER_05]: You said exactly the same thing before the last election.

178
00:12:01,455 --> 00:12:03,598
[SPEAKER_05]: We have no plans to raise VAT.

179
00:12:03,979 --> 00:12:07,284
[SPEAKER_05]: You said it to my face twice at the time of the last election.

180
00:12:07,945 --> 00:12:11,751
[SPEAKER_05]: And then the moment you got into government, you did raise VAT.

181
00:12:11,731 --> 00:12:14,635
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, there is a crucial difference on this occasion.

182
00:12:14,695 --> 00:12:15,476
[SPEAKER_04]: We are the government.

183
00:12:15,837 --> 00:12:18,100
[SPEAKER_04]: We've been able to look very carefully at the books.

184
00:12:18,160 --> 00:12:20,904
[SPEAKER_04]: We know what is necessary in the next Parliament.

185
00:12:21,264 --> 00:12:28,173
[SPEAKER_04]: And our plans do not involve tax increases on VAT or national insurance or income tax.

186
00:12:28,213 --> 00:12:29,375
[SPEAKER_04]: It's very clear about that.

187
00:12:29,395 --> 00:12:30,356
[SPEAKER_04]: We know what needs to be done.

188
00:12:30,376 --> 00:12:34,482
[SPEAKER_04]: And let me explain, because I think people watching at home want to know, what is the scale?

189
00:12:34,462 --> 00:12:35,444
[SPEAKER_04]: of what needs to be done.

190
00:12:35,484 --> 00:12:40,431
[SPEAKER_04]: We need to save, for the next two years, one out of every £100 that the government spends.

191
00:12:40,852 --> 00:12:51,288
[SPEAKER_04]: Now I think it is the right approach to try and find £1 of waste in £100 of government spending, rather than to put up everybody's taxes, which is what my political opponents want to do.

192
00:12:51,328 --> 00:12:52,089
[SPEAKER_04]: So you've got a choice.

193
00:12:52,811 --> 00:12:57,979
[SPEAKER_04]: Bear down on waste and get public spending under control, or put up taxes with my opponents.

194
00:12:58,019 --> 00:12:58,900
[SPEAKER_04]: That's the choice.

195
00:13:00,162 --> 00:13:03,848
[SPEAKER_05]: But again, you said one thing, and you did another.

196
00:13:04,389 --> 00:13:13,243
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we said that the most important task for the government was to get the economy growing, was to get jobs growing, and was to get the deficit down.

197
00:13:13,323 --> 00:13:17,429
[SPEAKER_04]: And I would say on any analysis, and we've had to take, we had an appalling inheritance.

198
00:13:17,750 --> 00:13:22,457
[SPEAKER_04]: We inherited a situation where Britain's budget deficit was forecast to be bigger than Greece's.

199
00:13:22,437 --> 00:13:24,022
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, we had to take difficult decisions.

200
00:13:24,222 --> 00:13:26,368
[SPEAKER_04]: I will defend all of those decisions.

201
00:13:26,408 --> 00:13:31,021
[SPEAKER_04]: Difficult ones, ones that were hard to take, but the right thing for the country.

202
00:13:31,062 --> 00:13:37,881
[SPEAKER_04]: And the result, there's a connection between the difficult decisions we had to take and the fact that we now have the fastest growing economy

203
00:13:37,861 --> 00:13:39,804
[SPEAKER_04]: of any major Western economy.

204
00:13:40,144 --> 00:13:42,487
[SPEAKER_04]: We've created 2 million private sector jobs.

205
00:13:42,788 --> 00:13:44,791
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got 750,000 more businesses.

206
00:13:44,831 --> 00:13:46,854
[SPEAKER_04]: The British economy is working.

207
00:13:46,914 --> 00:13:52,101
[SPEAKER_04]: Now we need to make sure that people can... What I want is an economy that doesn't just look good on the page.

208
00:13:52,221 --> 00:14:00,392
[SPEAKER_04]: I want people to feel that they can get a job, they can have a livelihood, they can buy a home, they can get a good school place for their children, they can enjoy a retirement.

209
00:14:00,433 --> 00:14:01,174
[SPEAKER_04]: Those are the things.

210
00:14:01,194 --> 00:14:04,078
[SPEAKER_04]: But that's what this plan, Jeremy, is all about.

211
00:14:04,098 --> 00:14:06,501
[SPEAKER_05]: In the spirit of transparency,

212
00:14:06,818 --> 00:14:12,004
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you tell us where this £12 billion in welfare cuts is going to come from?

213
00:14:12,285 --> 00:14:13,246
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, let me explain.

214
00:14:13,726 --> 00:14:20,615
[SPEAKER_04]: We've said that there's a £30 billion adjustment that needs to be made, and the other political parties have voted for this too.

215
00:14:21,035 --> 00:14:33,090
[SPEAKER_04]: And we've said that breaks down into £13 billion that needs to be saved in government departments, £12 billion in welfare, and £5 billion from cracking down on tax evasion and aggressive tax avoidance.

216
00:14:33,110 --> 00:14:35,813
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, when it comes to the welfare, we've identified

217
00:14:35,793 --> 00:14:42,561
[SPEAKER_04]: for instance, freezing in-work benefits, like unemployment benefit, for two years to raise some of that money.

218
00:14:42,942 --> 00:14:47,768
[SPEAKER_04]: But the £12 billion, right, that, the £12 billion... £10 billion of which you've yet to explain.

219
00:14:47,788 --> 00:14:54,676
[SPEAKER_04]: That compares with £20 billion that was saved in the last parliament, in this current parliament, by this government on welfare.

220
00:14:54,696 --> 00:15:00,263
[SPEAKER_04]: So this is well within the range of what we can do if we continue with the sort of plans that we put in place.

221
00:15:00,283 --> 00:15:02,526
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you know where these cuts will fall?

222
00:15:02,506 --> 00:15:07,518
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we know that it is possible to make the savings in welfare, like we made.

223
00:15:07,538 --> 00:15:09,042
[SPEAKER_04]: We made 20 billion in welfare savings.

224
00:15:09,062 --> 00:15:14,475
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm sorry, I don't want to be rude, but do you know and you're not telling us, or do you not know?

225
00:15:14,535 --> 00:15:20,650
[SPEAKER_04]: We know there will be difficult decisions, and we'll have to go through every part of the welfare budget.

226
00:15:20,630 --> 00:15:28,986
[SPEAKER_04]: but we believe just as we saved £20 billion in welfare in this Parliament, we will be able to find a further £10 billion of welfare savings in the next Parliament.

227
00:15:29,006 --> 00:15:30,710
[SPEAKER_04]: Let me give you some more examples.

228
00:15:30,750 --> 00:15:38,805
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to cut the welfare cap we put in place, saying no family should get more than £26,000 a year in welfare.

229
00:15:38,825 --> 00:15:40,228
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to reduce that to £23,000.

230
00:15:40,569 --> 00:15:41,811
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not within

231
00:15:41,791 --> 00:15:44,478
[SPEAKER_04]: We think that's the right thing to do.

232
00:15:44,879 --> 00:15:58,635
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to say when it comes to young people that young people when they leave school they should be either earning or learning, they should be doing an apprenticeship, looking at higher education, they shouldn't be able to go straight on to unemployment benefit and housing benefit.

233
00:15:58,615 --> 00:16:02,300
[SPEAKER_04]: All of these things... Changing welfare, Jeremy, isn't just about saving money.

234
00:16:02,340 --> 00:16:02,581
[SPEAKER_04]: No.

235
00:16:02,741 --> 00:16:05,344
[SPEAKER_04]: It's about trying to help people's lives.

236
00:16:05,364 --> 00:16:05,985
[SPEAKER_04]: You give no deep.

237
00:16:06,025 --> 00:16:10,652
[SPEAKER_05]: It's about trying to... Talk about transparency and you don't tell us what you're going to do.

238
00:16:11,313 --> 00:16:16,199
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me ask you a very simple question about something else, about foreign policy, because we're going to be out of time shortly.

239
00:16:17,441 --> 00:16:20,185
[SPEAKER_05]: What do you think has been your biggest foreign policy disaster?

240
00:16:20,992 --> 00:16:25,697
[SPEAKER_04]: Other people, I'm sure, will highlight difficult things that we've had to deal with.

241
00:16:25,838 --> 00:16:27,580
[SPEAKER_04]: But what did you find the greatest reverse?

242
00:16:27,860 --> 00:16:40,094
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I would argue that some good things we've done are cutting the European budget, first government to achieve that, getting out of the Euro bailout scheme so British taxpayers aren't giving money to Greece.

243
00:16:40,114 --> 00:16:41,496
[SPEAKER_04]: Those, I would say, are successes.

244
00:16:42,057 --> 00:16:45,360
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we've got a very challenging situation today in Libya.

245
00:16:45,561 --> 00:16:47,623
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it was right to get rid of...

246
00:16:47,603 --> 00:16:51,811
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you regret going to Libya and promising the people... You promised.

247
00:16:51,831 --> 00:16:53,174
[SPEAKER_05]: You used the word promise.

248
00:16:53,214 --> 00:16:58,725
[SPEAKER_05]: The people of Britain and France will stand by you as you build your country and your democracy.

249
00:16:58,745 --> 00:16:59,707
[SPEAKER_05]: Those were your words.

250
00:16:59,867 --> 00:17:00,909
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you regret saying that?

251
00:17:00,949 --> 00:17:01,170
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

252
00:17:01,190 --> 00:17:02,813
[SPEAKER_05]: You haven't even got an embassy in Libya.

253
00:17:02,893 --> 00:17:03,975
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't regret saying that.

254
00:17:03,955 --> 00:17:04,255
[SPEAKER_04]: that.

255
00:17:04,276 --> 00:17:12,048
[SPEAKER_04]: First of all, I think it was right, with France and America, to stop Colonel Gaddafi when he was going to butcher his own people in Benghazi.

256
00:17:12,088 --> 00:17:21,123
[SPEAKER_04]: If we had not stepped in, if I hadn't ordered those aeroplanes into the sky, we would have seen a massive catastrophe in Benghazi of people butchered.

257
00:17:21,143 --> 00:17:22,145
[SPEAKER_04]: It was the right thing to do.

258
00:17:22,806 --> 00:17:23,888
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't accept

259
00:17:23,868 --> 00:17:26,330
[SPEAKER_04]: that we left the Libyan people after that.

260
00:17:26,410 --> 00:17:30,514
[SPEAKER_04]: We put in aid, we put in military training, we put in political assistance.

261
00:17:30,754 --> 00:17:36,118
[SPEAKER_04]: It just hasn't been possible to date to get the different parties in Libya... Christians are being beheaded on the beach.

262
00:17:36,158 --> 00:17:47,568
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, it hasn't been possible to get the different Libyan parts of government together, to get the warlords to put down their weapons, but we're still trying, even now, with people out there, trying to bring that about.

263
00:17:47,608 --> 00:17:51,051
[SPEAKER_04]: But it has been, I accept, a very difficult situation.

264
00:17:51,071 --> 00:17:53,453
[SPEAKER_05]: Can I ask you one quick question about Europe?

265
00:17:54,125 --> 00:18:02,839
[SPEAKER_05]: What would it take for you to vote no in a referendum on our continued participation in the European Union?

266
00:18:02,859 --> 00:18:09,229
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, if I didn't think it was in Britain's interest to stay in the European Union, I wouldn't argue for our membership.

267
00:18:09,609 --> 00:18:15,238
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think the situation today is that what we need is a reform of the European Union.

268
00:18:15,218 --> 00:18:24,034
[SPEAKER_04]: and then a referendum where the British people, not me, but the British people watching at home, they have the choice in an in-out referendum by the end of 2017.

269
00:18:24,575 --> 00:18:28,382
[SPEAKER_04]: By implication then, surely our current membership is intolerable.

270
00:18:28,402 --> 00:18:31,928
[SPEAKER_04]: No, what I think is we need to improve on our current membership.

271
00:18:31,908 --> 00:18:40,325
[SPEAKER_04]: This organisation works to an extent for us, we get the trade, we get important cooperation, but Europe isn't working properly.

272
00:18:40,345 --> 00:18:42,069
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why we need the renegotiation.

273
00:18:42,109 --> 00:18:47,841
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why I think those who say just have a referendum straight away, I think would be giving the British

274
00:18:47,821 --> 00:18:48,883
[SPEAKER_04]: people a false choice.

275
00:18:48,903 --> 00:18:53,030
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to give a proper choice, stay in a reformed organisation or leave.

276
00:18:53,230 --> 00:18:54,773
[SPEAKER_04]: But it will be the British people's choice.

277
00:18:54,793 --> 00:19:04,750
[SPEAKER_04]: I will make this point Jeremy, there's only one way to get a referendum and that is to make sure I'm Prime Minister after the next election because none of my principal opponents will promise a referendum.

278
00:19:05,438 --> 00:19:07,902
[SPEAKER_05]: You've said you're not going to stand for a third term.

279
00:19:08,684 --> 00:19:27,818
[SPEAKER_05]: That means that a vote for Cameron is a vote, if you're successful, for Cameron as leader of his party and Prime Minister, perhaps, for two, three, four years, after which it's Boris Johnson or George Osborne or Theresa May or Sajid Javid or Uncle Tom Cobley.

280
00:19:27,798 --> 00:19:33,686
[SPEAKER_04]: If you vote Conservative, I've said I will serve every day of a full second term.

281
00:19:34,027 --> 00:19:40,936
[SPEAKER_04]: What I was doing in that interview was just giving an honest answer to an honest question, because I think people need to know that sort of thing.

282
00:19:41,257 --> 00:19:45,182
[SPEAKER_04]: Are you one of those leaders who, like Chairman Mao, thinks you can go on and on and on and on?

283
00:19:45,563 --> 00:19:49,048
[SPEAKER_04]: Or actually, do you think, look, I'm really passionate about what I'm doing.

284
00:19:49,068 --> 00:19:50,510
[SPEAKER_04]: I think we're turning this country around.

285
00:19:50,530 --> 00:19:54,295
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm passionate about having another term, completing this vital work.

286
00:19:54,275 --> 00:20:02,805
[SPEAKER_04]: But after that, 10 years, two terms, I think politicians do have a date by which they need to say, well, I think it's time for someone else to take over.

287
00:20:02,886 --> 00:20:06,090
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm not some person who thinks that you just, you're indispensable.

288
00:20:06,310 --> 00:20:07,131
[SPEAKER_04]: We're not indispensable.

289
00:20:07,191 --> 00:20:08,132
[SPEAKER_04]: It's important to remember that.

290
00:20:08,512 --> 00:20:09,574
[SPEAKER_05]: David Cameron, thank you.

291
00:20:09,974 --> 00:20:20,367
[SPEAKER_05]: Now coming next, questions to Mr. Cameron from our studio audience.

292
00:24:32,695 --> 00:24:36,261
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome back to Cameron and Miliband live, the battle for number 10.

293
00:24:36,642 --> 00:24:43,674
[SPEAKER_10]: The Prime Minister has been interviewed by Jeremy Paxman and now it's the turn of our studio audience to put their questions to him.

294
00:24:44,014 --> 00:24:45,998
[SPEAKER_10]: So without further ado, Prime Minister, here we go.

295
00:24:46,038 --> 00:24:48,342
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's start with Matthew Brown.

296
00:24:48,362 --> 00:24:49,404
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you, Matthew?

297
00:24:49,464 --> 00:24:50,926
[SPEAKER_10]: There's Matthew.

298
00:24:50,966 --> 00:24:52,389
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's have your question, Matthew.

299
00:24:52,769 --> 00:24:56,155
[SPEAKER_04]: Prime Minister, what do you think are Ed Miliband's best qualities?

300
00:24:58,126 --> 00:25:00,891
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, that's a tricky one to start with, but thank you, Matthew, for the question.

301
00:25:01,552 --> 00:25:09,327
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, I think all of us who put ourselves forward all actually believe in serving the public, in trying to do the right thing.

302
00:25:09,748 --> 00:25:20,067
[SPEAKER_04]: We disagree with each other, sometimes passionately, sometimes, as yesterday in the House of Commons, rather noisily, but we all believe in public service and trying to do the right thing for our country.

303
00:25:20,047 --> 00:25:39,760
[SPEAKER_04]: One thing I admire about Ed is that when we had to take difficult decisions about sending British forces in to help with others to try and defeat ISIL, the murderous death cult in Iraq, he stepped forward and said, yes, this is the right thing to do, David, let's do that together and vote together in the House of Commons, and I admired that.

304
00:25:39,740 --> 00:25:41,605
[SPEAKER_10]: But you did call him weak and despicable, didn't you?

305
00:25:41,885 --> 00:25:48,963
[SPEAKER_04]: We do sometimes in the House of Commons use phrases that perhaps afterwards we think perhaps was a bit over the top.

306
00:25:48,983 --> 00:25:50,306
[SPEAKER_04]: Was that over the top?

307
00:25:50,326 --> 00:25:53,333
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I remember the same day he called me dodgy and something else.

308
00:25:53,393 --> 00:25:54,055
[SPEAKER_04]: So sometimes...

309
00:25:54,336 --> 00:25:56,922
[SPEAKER_04]: I took my children yesterday and...

310
00:25:56,902 --> 00:26:04,972
[SPEAKER_04]: Nancy and Elwyn, they're 9 and 11, and they said afterwards, you know, Dad, if we behave like that at school, you know, it wouldn't be so good.

311
00:26:05,112 --> 00:26:07,114
[SPEAKER_04]: So I try to explain, sometimes it gets a bit heated.

312
00:26:07,235 --> 00:26:14,283
[SPEAKER_04]: There is a point to it, though, which is it's the time of the week when the Prime Minister's got to demonstrate that you're across all the issues.

313
00:26:14,403 --> 00:26:21,832
[SPEAKER_04]: And so it does make the government accountable to Parliament in a way that if you're not across the issues, then things will change pretty quickly.

314
00:26:21,872 --> 00:26:24,816
[SPEAKER_04]: So it does have a point, but we don't always behave as well as we should.

315
00:26:24,796 --> 00:26:27,661
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's bring in Bridget Sam Bailey next, should we?

316
00:26:27,681 --> 00:26:29,524
[SPEAKER_10]: I think Bridget's there in the front row.

317
00:26:29,544 --> 00:26:29,765
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

318
00:26:29,785 --> 00:26:30,185
[SPEAKER_12]: Hi, Bridget.

319
00:26:30,205 --> 00:26:34,473
[SPEAKER_12]: Prime Minister, in a few months' time, I would be 79.

320
00:26:34,733 --> 00:26:37,478
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm a retired professional.

321
00:26:38,881 --> 00:26:46,534
[SPEAKER_12]: Following a road traffic accident, I've been left with physical challenges, yet I remain proactive in the community.

322
00:26:46,514 --> 00:26:56,030
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm passionate about the provision of care for the elderly, and I feel that we should be treated with dignity and respect.

323
00:26:56,752 --> 00:27:08,472
[SPEAKER_12]: Would you, Prime Minister, consider it appropriate to appoint a cabinet minister for older people, one who would show empathy with older people?

324
00:27:08,688 --> 00:27:13,816
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, Bridget, first of all, thank you for your advocacy for these causes, because they do really matter.

325
00:27:14,277 --> 00:27:23,633
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think making sure we treat retired people with dignity and security in their old age, after a full working life, is one of the most important things we can do as a country.

326
00:27:23,733 --> 00:27:32,367
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's why I've been so clear that the pensioner benefits, like the free TV licences, the free prescriptions, the winter fuel payments, they will continue for everybody.

327
00:27:32,347 --> 00:27:35,656
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it should be your right and we need to make that very clear.

328
00:27:36,118 --> 00:27:42,355
[SPEAKER_04]: I was asked this question the other day about should we have a dedicated older person's representative in the cabinet.

329
00:27:43,800 --> 00:27:46,467
[SPEAKER_04]: I will think about it but I'm a little bit worried about it on this basis.

330
00:27:46,868 --> 00:27:47,470
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't want

331
00:27:47,450 --> 00:27:52,054
[SPEAKER_04]: older people's concerns to be sort of restricted to one person in the cabinet.

332
00:27:52,114 --> 00:27:57,179
[SPEAKER_04]: I want every one of my ministers to be thinking, how do we treat senior citizens properly?

333
00:27:57,199 --> 00:28:02,103
[SPEAKER_04]: I want my health minister to be thinking, how do we treat people in our hospitals and in our care homes?

334
00:28:02,123 --> 00:28:03,084
[SPEAKER_04]: Are we doing this right?

335
00:28:03,524 --> 00:28:10,391
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to make sure that our education minister is thinking about through life education that some people want to continue with forever.

336
00:28:11,031 --> 00:28:17,457
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to make sure that our defence minister is thinking really carefully about veterans and their needs as they grow older.

337
00:28:17,437 --> 00:28:24,967
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'd be worried about possibly having one person and saying they were the only person who thought about older people.

338
00:28:25,027 --> 00:28:36,022
[SPEAKER_04]: In the end, as I said to this meeting the other day, if we're not doing right by older people, don't blame all my men, blame me, because I lead the government and I think we've got to get this right.

339
00:28:36,402 --> 00:28:45,334
[SPEAKER_04]: But pensioners have been absolutely key to this government about uprating pension in line with earnings, prices, or 2.5%, the so-called triple lock.

340
00:28:45,314 --> 00:28:49,101
[SPEAKER_04]: so that pensioners have been protected from some of the difficult decisions we've had to take.

341
00:28:49,301 --> 00:28:50,163
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Prime Minister.

342
00:28:50,203 --> 00:28:52,567
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's bring in Tom Cosgrove next.

343
00:28:52,587 --> 00:28:53,088
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, Tom.

344
00:28:53,108 --> 00:28:54,811
[SPEAKER_10]: You approached us via the Sky News app.

345
00:28:54,831 --> 00:28:55,352
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you, Tom?

346
00:28:56,714 --> 00:28:57,015
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, Tom.

347
00:28:57,035 --> 00:28:58,337
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question for the Prime Minister?

348
00:28:58,738 --> 00:29:02,885
[SPEAKER_15]: It has been argued that we haven't seen anything yet in terms of cuts to public services.

349
00:29:03,406 --> 00:29:06,732
[SPEAKER_15]: How intense will these be for the majority Conservative government?

350
00:29:07,268 --> 00:29:31,745
[SPEAKER_04]: What I'd say is that we have had to make difficult decisions, and I didn't... A lot of those decisions I didn't want to have to make, but I became Prime Minister at a time when the economy was close to the brink, when our budget deficit was forecast actually to be higher than Greece's, and we had to make important decisions to get the deficit down, because a big deficit means higher taxes, it means higher mortgage rates, it means lost jobs, it means an economy in chaos, and I wanted to stop that.

351
00:29:32,185 --> 00:29:36,752
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, what we've done so far has got the deficit down by half, as I was saying to Jeremy,

352
00:29:36,732 --> 00:29:41,558
[SPEAKER_04]: And what we need to do in the next two years is basically similar to what we've done so far.

353
00:29:41,638 --> 00:29:48,987
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got to find one pound out of every hundred the government spends and save that, rather than putting up people's taxes.

354
00:29:49,407 --> 00:29:56,856
[SPEAKER_04]: So if you think of the department spending changes, it's similar to what we've had to do in previous years, and similarly for welfare.

355
00:29:57,016 --> 00:29:58,318
[SPEAKER_04]: It is achievable.

356
00:29:58,298 --> 00:30:01,042
[SPEAKER_04]: I wouldn't stand here and say that if I didn't believe that.

357
00:30:01,342 --> 00:30:08,873
[SPEAKER_04]: I really want to do this without putting up taxes on hard-working people, because you don't tax your way to growth, you don't tax your way to jobs.

358
00:30:09,514 --> 00:30:21,671
[SPEAKER_04]: We want to keep the strong economy, make these savings, and make sure that we do put aside money for a rainy day, so that when the next crisis hits, and crises do come from time to time, we don't get pushed over the edge.

359
00:30:22,071 --> 00:30:24,154
[SPEAKER_04]: And that would be so irresponsible.

360
00:30:24,134 --> 00:30:31,402
[SPEAKER_04]: Because in the end, we've got to make sure we're not just doing right for this generation, we're doing right for our children and grandchildren.

361
00:30:31,422 --> 00:30:34,105
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't want to load debts on their heads that they won't be able to pay.

362
00:30:34,586 --> 00:30:47,139
[SPEAKER_04]: So what we're suggesting is manageable, it's doable, it will require efficiencies, but we can also make important commitments, like saying the NHS is special, that will get extra money every year as long as I'm Prime Minister.

363
00:30:47,159 --> 00:30:52,285
[SPEAKER_10]: Presumably, Tom, you would want a specific example, would you, of where the Prime Minister is going to save money, where the cuts might be?

364
00:30:52,265 --> 00:30:54,168
[SPEAKER_10]: There you go.

365
00:30:54,388 --> 00:31:01,198
[SPEAKER_04]: I think a good example of saying, look, you know, benefits, in-work benefits, things like unemployment benefits should be frozen for two years.

366
00:31:01,258 --> 00:31:02,700
[SPEAKER_04]: That will save £2 billion.

367
00:31:03,040 --> 00:31:14,577
[SPEAKER_04]: That isn't an easy decision to make, but I think it's important people can see it's better off, you know, that people are better off in work and we try and keep on creating those jobs as we've done.

368
00:31:14,557 --> 00:31:17,041
[SPEAKER_04]: And we find savings, including from efficiency.

369
00:31:17,081 --> 00:31:22,328
[SPEAKER_04]: This Parliament, we've saved something like £20 billion by just being a bit smarter.

370
00:31:22,829 --> 00:31:27,796
[SPEAKER_04]: We still don't have one company that owns all the government's buildings and makes sure we use them efficiently.

371
00:31:27,816 --> 00:31:28,878
[SPEAKER_04]: So let's do things like that.

372
00:31:29,399 --> 00:31:31,662
[SPEAKER_04]: Businesses have to do this every year.

373
00:31:31,682 --> 00:31:35,147
[SPEAKER_04]: They don't get more efficient and then say, that's it, I've finished.

374
00:31:35,127 --> 00:31:37,850
[SPEAKER_04]: They think every year, how can we save money?

375
00:31:37,970 --> 00:31:41,695
[SPEAKER_04]: How can we provide a better service without spending so much money?

376
00:31:42,155 --> 00:31:45,379
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. We've had to do that in... One example, just quickly, policing.

377
00:31:45,519 --> 00:31:45,900
[SPEAKER_10]: Very, very good.

378
00:31:45,920 --> 00:31:47,001
[SPEAKER_04]: The police have done a brilliant job.

379
00:31:47,081 --> 00:31:47,422
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm glad you are.

380
00:31:47,522 --> 00:31:52,428
[SPEAKER_10]: We have had... Prime Minister, while you're talking about policing, let me bring in Zaid Malik, who is a police officer.

381
00:31:52,948 --> 00:31:54,210
[SPEAKER_10]: It's almost as if we planned it.

382
00:31:54,330 --> 00:31:54,890
[SPEAKER_10]: Very good.

383
00:31:54,991 --> 00:31:55,491
[SPEAKER_10]: And we didn't.

384
00:31:55,611 --> 00:31:56,372
[SPEAKER_10]: He's from the West Midlands.

385
00:31:56,392 --> 00:31:56,633
[SPEAKER_10]: Where is he?

386
00:31:56,653 --> 00:31:59,256
[SPEAKER_10]: You've been a police officer for 22 years, haven't you, Zaid?

387
00:31:59,276 --> 00:31:59,716
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you?

388
00:31:59,736 --> 00:32:00,938
[SPEAKER_18]: I have, Kay, thank you.

389
00:32:01,118 --> 00:32:03,801
[SPEAKER_18]: Prime Minister, my question to yourself is,

390
00:32:03,781 --> 00:32:16,137
[SPEAKER_18]: Would the Conservatives reverse their decision and come back to the police service, which is now more than ever overburdened and walking a tightrope without a safety net?

391
00:32:16,505 --> 00:32:20,290
[SPEAKER_04]: I was about... First of all, Zane, thank you very much for your service in the police.

392
00:32:20,530 --> 00:32:27,179
[SPEAKER_04]: I know that you put your lives on the line every day to keep us safe, and I have huge respect for what the police do for us.

393
00:32:27,620 --> 00:32:31,125
[SPEAKER_04]: But I was about to say what a brilliant example the police have been.

394
00:32:31,185 --> 00:32:38,735
[SPEAKER_04]: Over the last five years, we did have to make reductions in spending on the police, so police budgets came down by some 20%.

395
00:32:39,556 --> 00:32:44,082
[SPEAKER_04]: But at the same time, the police have done such a good job that crime has come down.

396
00:32:44,062 --> 00:32:45,163
[SPEAKER_04]: by almost 20%.

397
00:32:45,904 --> 00:32:50,551
[SPEAKER_04]: We managed to get officers out from desk jobs onto the streets.

398
00:32:50,891 --> 00:32:53,454
[SPEAKER_04]: We put more civilians into some of those roles.

399
00:32:53,815 --> 00:33:00,564
[SPEAKER_04]: We made sure, and the police did this themselves, they combined, forces were combining and ordering equipment and things together.

400
00:33:00,944 --> 00:33:10,677
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think there's still some more efficiency that we can get out of that, but in the end, we've got to back the British police, who are the best in the world, who do a great job, and they'll always have my support.

401
00:33:10,859 --> 00:33:16,606
[SPEAKER_10]: As far as Lincolnshire police are concerned, though, Prime Minister, the chief constable there said that it's on the verge of collapse.

402
00:33:16,626 --> 00:33:17,887
[SPEAKER_10]: He said that last December.

403
00:33:18,648 --> 00:33:19,650
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I just...

404
00:33:19,670 --> 00:33:20,511
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't accept that.

405
00:33:20,531 --> 00:33:22,393
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I think, you know, I understand... Is he wrong?

406
00:33:22,413 --> 00:33:23,274
[SPEAKER_04]: ..that they're under pressure.

407
00:33:23,294 --> 00:33:23,594
[SPEAKER_04]: Is he wrong?

408
00:33:23,714 --> 00:33:35,969
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I think if you look at Lincolnshire, in that county as well, you know, crime has come down because the police are doing a great job, and there's more we need to do, using modern technology, to make sure that crime continues to fall under this government.

409
00:33:35,989 --> 00:33:39,313
[SPEAKER_04]: And if we do that, then we should be saving money as well.

410
00:33:40,576 --> 00:33:41,238
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's bring in...

411
00:33:41,559 --> 00:33:42,563
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Prime Minister.

412
00:33:42,723 --> 00:33:44,088
[SPEAKER_10]: Were you happy with that response?

413
00:33:45,654 --> 00:33:46,537
[SPEAKER_18]: No comment.

414
00:33:46,557 --> 00:33:50,009
[SPEAKER_10]: OK. Rosemary Fraser is joining us now.

415
00:33:50,029 --> 00:33:51,093
[SPEAKER_10]: Hello to you, Rosemary.

416
00:33:51,113 --> 00:33:51,494
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you?

417
00:33:51,534 --> 00:33:52,678
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question?

418
00:33:53,249 --> 00:33:54,851
[SPEAKER_14]: Good evening, Prime Minister.

419
00:33:55,191 --> 00:33:56,893
[SPEAKER_14]: Hi, Rosemary.

420
00:33:56,913 --> 00:33:56,973
[SPEAKER_14]: Hi.

421
00:33:56,993 --> 00:34:05,382
[SPEAKER_14]: It's 20 years this year since the passing of the Disability Discrimination Act in the UK, yet if you're disabled, you're still twice as likely to be unemployed.

422
00:34:06,083 --> 00:34:13,130
[SPEAKER_14]: It's getting harder year on year to get vital social care support and attitudes towards disabled people are hardening and hardening.

423
00:34:13,551 --> 00:34:19,257
[SPEAKER_14]: I'd just like to know what you would do going forward to change that for Britain's 11 million disabled people.

424
00:34:19,237 --> 00:34:30,412
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I have a very simple view about this, which is we should do everything we can to help disabled people face as few disadvantages as possible and to get genuine equality in our country.

425
00:34:31,073 --> 00:34:42,409
[SPEAKER_04]: The Disability Discrimination Act was brought forward by my good friend and colleague William Hague 20 years ago and I think it has led to some really good changes, but you're right, the job isn't done.

426
00:34:42,389 --> 00:34:47,296
[SPEAKER_04]: One of the things I think we need to focus on is, as you say, getting more disabled people into work.

427
00:34:47,536 --> 00:34:48,858
[SPEAKER_04]: This year has been a good year.

428
00:34:48,918 --> 00:34:52,823
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got, I think, 140,000 more disabled people have got jobs.

429
00:34:53,104 --> 00:34:58,912
[SPEAKER_04]: But the gap between the disabled unemployment rate and the unemployment rate for the whole country is still too big.

430
00:34:58,952 --> 00:35:01,815
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to see that cut in half over the next five years.

431
00:35:01,836 --> 00:35:07,824
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think we can do that, but we need a culture change from employers as much as from anybody.

432
00:35:07,844 --> 00:35:10,287
[SPEAKER_04]: There are some employers who are absolutely brilliant,

433
00:35:10,267 --> 00:35:17,500
[SPEAKER_04]: who really go out there and want to recruit disabled people because they know if they don't, they're missing out on some of the brightest, best talent in our country.

434
00:35:17,880 --> 00:35:26,095
[SPEAKER_04]: But not all employers are that good, and that's why we've established something called Disability Confident to try and encourage all employers to take this approach.

435
00:35:26,135 --> 00:35:30,823
[SPEAKER_04]: So I would say we've done some good work, we've got more to do, but in the end,

436
00:35:30,803 --> 00:35:34,631
[SPEAKER_04]: It all comes back to the bigger picture of a strong and growing economy.

437
00:35:34,651 --> 00:35:39,461
[SPEAKER_04]: If we keep the economy strong, if we keep creating jobs, we can keep solving some of these issues.

438
00:35:39,742 --> 00:35:42,347
[SPEAKER_10]: Asking your specific question, we'll come back to the economy.

439
00:35:42,427 --> 00:35:44,531
[SPEAKER_10]: Are you happy with their response, Rosemary?

440
00:35:44,772 --> 00:35:49,963
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm partially happy with the response, but I still think there's an awful lot more that needs to be done.

441
00:35:50,404 --> 00:35:51,546
[SPEAKER_14]: You mentioned employment.

442
00:35:51,526 --> 00:35:57,302
[SPEAKER_14]: Social care is vital to help people get into and flourish in employment.

443
00:35:57,743 --> 00:35:59,869
[SPEAKER_14]: Year on year that's becoming more and more difficult.

444
00:36:00,290 --> 00:36:03,198
[SPEAKER_14]: You know, the Independent Living Fund was closed.

445
00:36:04,060 --> 00:36:07,830
[SPEAKER_04]: That really helps a lot of people stay in employment.

446
00:36:07,810 --> 00:36:10,374
[SPEAKER_04]: that local councils have the resources to do this.

447
00:36:10,394 --> 00:36:15,021
[SPEAKER_04]: We've just established this new fund, the Better Care Fund, that starts on the 1st of April.

448
00:36:15,041 --> 00:36:20,529
[SPEAKER_04]: It's got £5 billion in it to try and bring health and social care together more in our country.

449
00:36:20,910 --> 00:36:23,293
[SPEAKER_04]: And that could help with some of the issues that you're raising.

450
00:36:23,313 --> 00:36:24,515
[SPEAKER_04]: But thank you for the question.

451
00:36:24,535 --> 00:36:27,279
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's bring in Cara Montero now.

452
00:36:27,319 --> 00:36:28,361
[SPEAKER_10]: Hello to you, Cara.

453
00:36:28,381 --> 00:36:28,861
[SPEAKER_10]: Good evening.

454
00:36:28,962 --> 00:36:29,783
[SPEAKER_10]: Good evening, Prime Minister.

455
00:36:29,803 --> 00:36:31,245
[SPEAKER_10]: Just behind the camera there, Prime Minister.

456
00:36:31,265 --> 00:36:31,826
[SPEAKER_10]: Hello.

457
00:36:31,846 --> 00:36:37,294
[SPEAKER_11]: How are you going to convince the British public to not opt out of the EU?

458
00:36:37,696 --> 00:36:43,686
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the best way, first of all Cara, thank you for the question, we were just getting into it with Jeremy back there.

459
00:36:44,467 --> 00:36:51,699
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, I think Britain is at its best when we're out there trading and cooperating and working with others in the world.

460
00:36:51,879 --> 00:37:01,375
[SPEAKER_04]: We are an open country, we're a trading nation, we're part of all the most important networks, whether it's NATO or the G8 or the European Union, and we need them to work for us.

461
00:37:01,355 --> 00:37:08,186
[SPEAKER_04]: But I think the problem with the European Union at the moment, it's got some good aspects, but too many things that drive people mad.

462
00:37:08,546 --> 00:37:13,614
[SPEAKER_04]: People see that it's trying to become too much of a state rather than an organisation.

463
00:37:13,654 --> 00:37:15,016
[SPEAKER_04]: It's trying to take too much power.

464
00:37:15,397 --> 00:37:19,363
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think what we need is a new deal with Europe where we say, look,

465
00:37:19,343 --> 00:37:21,808
[SPEAKER_04]: We want to be in Europe for trade and cooperation.

466
00:37:21,828 --> 00:37:24,874
[SPEAKER_04]: We want that common market that we were promised all those years ago.

467
00:37:25,134 --> 00:37:27,679
[SPEAKER_04]: But we don't want to be part of an ever closer union.

468
00:37:27,959 --> 00:37:31,626
[SPEAKER_04]: Maybe the Eurozone countries with their own currency, maybe they need to do that.

469
00:37:32,007 --> 00:37:32,428
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't.

470
00:37:32,809 --> 00:37:34,672
[SPEAKER_04]: And we're going to keep the pound as our currency.

471
00:37:34,772 --> 00:37:36,977
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we will at least if I'm prime minister.

472
00:37:36,997 --> 00:37:38,820
[SPEAKER_04]: So if I can get a new deal,

473
00:37:38,800 --> 00:37:40,603
[SPEAKER_04]: from Europe, and I believe I can.

474
00:37:40,683 --> 00:37:44,169
[SPEAKER_04]: I've sat around that table for the last five years with those other countries.

475
00:37:44,370 --> 00:37:49,318
[SPEAKER_04]: If I can get that better deal, I think there's then a real prospect of saying to the British people, you choose.

476
00:37:49,578 --> 00:37:55,789
[SPEAKER_04]: You can stay in on this reformed basis, which would be good for Britain, or if you want, you can leave.

477
00:37:55,849 --> 00:37:59,195
[SPEAKER_04]: But the British public have got to be given another choice.

478
00:37:59,235 --> 00:38:02,260
[SPEAKER_04]: We haven't had one since 1975, and it's time we did.

479
00:38:02,240 --> 00:38:04,864
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, remember when we said, Prime Minister, about questions being quite short?

480
00:38:04,984 --> 00:38:05,666
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, sorry.

481
00:38:05,686 --> 00:38:06,627
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, we've got two more.

482
00:38:06,928 --> 00:38:08,109
[SPEAKER_10]: Karen Poole is with us.

483
00:38:08,210 --> 00:38:08,851
[SPEAKER_10]: Hi, Karen.

484
00:38:09,432 --> 00:38:09,552
[SPEAKER_09]: Hi.

485
00:38:10,293 --> 00:38:14,680
[SPEAKER_09]: Would you like to see more NHS services provided by private companies?

486
00:38:14,780 --> 00:38:15,742
[SPEAKER_04]: Sorry, Karen, I've lost you.

487
00:38:15,842 --> 00:38:16,343
[SPEAKER_04]: Where are you?

488
00:38:16,363 --> 00:38:16,783
[SPEAKER_04]: Karen's just here.

489
00:38:16,803 --> 00:38:17,785
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, sorry.

490
00:38:17,765 --> 00:38:23,295
[SPEAKER_09]: Would you like to see more NHS services provided by private companies, yes or no?

491
00:38:23,796 --> 00:38:34,795
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm happy if there are charities, if there are charities or independent organisations that can provide a great service free as part of the NHS.

492
00:38:34,775 --> 00:38:37,779
[SPEAKER_04]: then I think that if it's good health care, that's what matters to me.

493
00:38:38,300 --> 00:38:39,522
[SPEAKER_04]: I love our NHS.

494
00:38:39,542 --> 00:38:41,725
[SPEAKER_04]: It has done amazing things for my family.

495
00:38:41,825 --> 00:38:51,620
[SPEAKER_04]: I will never forget taking my desperately ill young son, Ivan, to hospital night after night, getting into A&E, getting amazing treatment, everything that they gave him.

496
00:38:51,840 --> 00:38:55,846
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to make sure that that is always there for families in our country.

497
00:38:56,227 --> 00:38:58,470
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, that would always be predominantly

498
00:38:58,450 --> 00:39:02,415
[SPEAKER_04]: A national health service provided by national health service providers.

499
00:39:02,515 --> 00:39:05,919
[SPEAKER_04]: The private sector, the independent sector, is a tiny proportion of the total.

500
00:39:05,939 --> 00:39:09,683
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it's gone from 5% to 6% under this government.

501
00:39:09,723 --> 00:39:10,705
[SPEAKER_04]: A tiny increase.

502
00:39:11,165 --> 00:39:20,256
[SPEAKER_04]: But if there are organisations, like for instance Marie Curie Cancer Care or Macmillan Nurses, who provide brilliant care for loved ones,

503
00:39:20,236 --> 00:39:32,254
[SPEAKER_04]: or hospices, which aren't part of the NHS, if there are great organisations like that, that are helping our loved ones, and they're free, and the NHS and our taxes are helping to pay for them, that's OK by me.

504
00:39:32,274 --> 00:39:34,537
[SPEAKER_10]: Lady with her hand up there in the blue dress.

505
00:39:34,597 --> 00:39:34,858
[SPEAKER_10]: Madam.

506
00:39:35,499 --> 00:39:35,759
[SPEAKER_04]: Hi there.

507
00:39:35,779 --> 00:39:37,181
[SPEAKER_10]: Just wait for the microphone, if you would.

508
00:39:37,201 --> 00:39:37,662
[SPEAKER_10]: There we go.

509
00:39:37,862 --> 00:39:39,324
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we can get a little bit closer to you.

510
00:39:39,364 --> 00:39:39,905
[SPEAKER_10]: There we are.

511
00:39:39,925 --> 00:39:40,466
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

512
00:39:40,506 --> 00:39:41,347
[SPEAKER_10]: What would you like to say?

513
00:39:41,848 --> 00:39:47,897
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm just a little bit confused, because I do remember very clearly five years ago that you made some very serious pledges.

514
00:39:48,147 --> 00:39:51,450
[SPEAKER_11]: about the NHS, and I saw your billboards, it's safe in our hands.

515
00:39:52,592 --> 00:39:58,317
[SPEAKER_11]: The no top-down reorganisation of the NHS, that clearly, the reality has been very, very different.

516
00:39:58,338 --> 00:40:01,521
[SPEAKER_11]: There has been huge top-down reorganisation of the NHS.

517
00:40:01,541 --> 00:40:05,605
[SPEAKER_11]: The no forced closure of local A&E maternity units was actually in your manifesto.

518
00:40:05,625 --> 00:40:11,251
[SPEAKER_11]: And where I live in my borough, we had to take you and your government to court to keep our hospital open.

519
00:40:11,751 --> 00:40:17,277
[SPEAKER_11]: So I feel very let down with conservative policy on the NHS, and I'm just wondering,

520
00:40:17,257 --> 00:40:22,884
[SPEAKER_11]: If you don't do what you say, the promises you made last time have been broken, as far as I'm concerned.

521
00:40:22,904 --> 00:40:24,346
[SPEAKER_11]: So how can we trust you next time?

522
00:40:24,386 --> 00:40:36,502
[SPEAKER_04]: What I'd say, the biggest promise we made about the NHS at a time when we were going to have to make difficult cuts in public spending, as anyone, Prime Minister, when I was Prime Minister, would have to do, we said, we will not cut the NHS.

523
00:40:36,622 --> 00:40:37,443
[SPEAKER_04]: And we haven't.

524
00:40:37,463 --> 00:40:43,430
[SPEAKER_04]: We've increased spending on the NHS by over £12.7 billion over the last five years.

525
00:40:43,791 --> 00:40:46,234
[SPEAKER_04]: And because this is a really important point, can I ask quickly,

526
00:40:46,214 --> 00:40:59,778
[SPEAKER_04]: What we did in terms of changing the NHS is we got rid of 20,000 bureaucrats in the NHS and we put that money into 9,000 more doctors and 7,000 more nurses and as a result we're treating more patients.

527
00:40:59,819 --> 00:41:01,742
[SPEAKER_04]: If you take something just like cancer,

528
00:41:01,722 --> 00:41:08,792
[SPEAKER_04]: We're seeing 460,000 more people and looking at their potential cancer than we were five years ago.

529
00:41:08,812 --> 00:41:15,000
[SPEAKER_04]: So the biggest promise we made, more money, safeguarding that money and treating more patients, has been kept.

530
00:41:15,040 --> 00:41:22,971
[SPEAKER_04]: And if you elect me again as your Prime Minister with a strong economy, because that's the key to afford this, we'll go on investing in our National Health Service.

531
00:41:23,272 --> 00:41:28,899
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, Prime Minister, we're almost out of time, but we've just got time for one more quick answer, if you would, please.

532
00:41:29,500 --> 00:41:38,551
[SPEAKER_10]: And that is from Lagdeep Jai Chand, who... She had actually lost her voice, Prime Minister, but she's persevered tonight so that she can ask you a question in person.

533
00:41:39,312 --> 00:41:42,716
[SPEAKER_10]: If you could redo one thing from your time as Prime Minister, what would it be?

534
00:41:43,978 --> 00:41:48,283
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, if you could redo one thing as your time as Prime Minister, what would it be?

535
00:41:48,466 --> 00:41:52,093
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, there's definitely the thing, as I said, I haven't delivered.

536
00:41:52,113 --> 00:41:56,761
[SPEAKER_04]: I promised better, less noise at Prime Minister's questions, more politeness.

537
00:41:56,781 --> 00:41:57,863
[SPEAKER_04]: That certainly didn't work out.

538
00:41:58,003 --> 00:41:59,125
[SPEAKER_04]: I fully accept that.

539
00:41:59,386 --> 00:42:08,803
[SPEAKER_04]: Look, I think the most important thing I've had to try and do is turn the economy around, get people into jobs, get the deficit down, get the economy growing, because we were on the brink.

540
00:42:08,783 --> 00:42:17,959
[SPEAKER_04]: And I wish that some of the things that we've done, like, for instance, the Help to Buy scheme that has got many more people able to buy their houses, I wish we'd done some of those things quicker.

541
00:42:18,420 --> 00:42:19,862
[SPEAKER_04]: I wish we'd done some of those things sooner.

542
00:42:20,283 --> 00:42:26,914
[SPEAKER_04]: Because in the end, you're going to have to make this huge choice in 42 days' time who runs the country.

543
00:42:26,994 --> 00:42:32,023
[SPEAKER_04]: And all I'd say, what I've learned in the last five years, is nothing that you want to do

544
00:42:32,577 --> 00:42:34,799
[SPEAKER_04]: will work without a strong and growing economy.

545
00:42:34,839 --> 00:42:39,943
[SPEAKER_04]: The schools we want for our children, the hospitals we want when we're ill, those things need the strong economy.

546
00:42:39,963 --> 00:42:41,484
[SPEAKER_10]: OK. Have you ever had three shredded wheat?

547
00:42:42,005 --> 00:42:43,266
[SPEAKER_04]: Have I ever had three shredded wheat?

548
00:42:43,286 --> 00:42:44,127
[SPEAKER_04]: I have, actually.

549
00:42:44,267 --> 00:42:46,869
[SPEAKER_04]: But that was a long time ago.

550
00:42:47,650 --> 00:42:48,230
[SPEAKER_10]: We're out of time.

551
00:42:48,370 --> 00:42:50,512
[SPEAKER_10]: Prime Minister, would you like to show your appreciation?

552
00:43:00,440 --> 00:43:00,841
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much.

553
00:43:00,861 --> 00:43:01,381
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Prime Minister.

554
00:43:01,401 --> 00:43:01,942
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much indeed.

555
00:43:01,962 --> 00:43:02,162
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

556
00:43:02,182 --> 00:43:02,382
Thank you.

557
00:43:03,526 --> 00:43:12,624
[SPEAKER_10]: Coming next, Ed Minibine will be taking more questions from our studio audience, so do stay tuned to us here on Sky and Channel 4.

558
00:43:12,644 --> 00:43:14,006
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much.

559
00:43:14,026 --> 00:43:21,501
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you very much indeed.

560
00:47:27,248 --> 00:47:45,009
[SPEAKER_10]: And again, welcome back to Cameron and Miliband Live, the battle for number 10.

561
00:47:45,049 --> 00:47:50,955
[SPEAKER_10]: Tonight, we've seen David Cameron face the questions of Jeremy Paxman and also those of our studio audience.

562
00:47:51,035 --> 00:47:53,438
[SPEAKER_10]: Now it's the turn of the Labour leader, Ed Miliband.

563
00:47:53,478 --> 00:47:56,682
[SPEAKER_10]: He is here in the studio and ready to meet our audience.

564
00:48:06,010 --> 00:48:09,780
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's see if they're still applauding by the end of this 18-minute section.

565
00:48:10,020 --> 00:48:11,184
[SPEAKER_10]: Paul Hickson, first of all.

566
00:48:11,204 --> 00:48:12,567
[SPEAKER_10]: Paul, you are retired, aren't you?

567
00:48:12,587 --> 00:48:13,409
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question?

568
00:48:13,750 --> 00:48:14,472
[SPEAKER_19]: Good evening.

569
00:48:15,014 --> 00:48:16,277
[SPEAKER_19]: My question is this.

570
00:48:16,858 --> 00:48:19,265
[SPEAKER_19]: You sound gloomy most of the time.

571
00:48:21,230 --> 00:48:22,112
[SPEAKER_19]: LAUGHTER

572
00:48:22,312 --> 00:48:23,654
[SPEAKER_19]: Are things really so bad?

573
00:48:23,674 --> 00:48:26,177
[SPEAKER_07]: No, but they could be a lot better.

574
00:48:26,938 --> 00:48:29,241
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is the big argument of this election.

575
00:48:30,062 --> 00:48:35,368
[SPEAKER_07]: I think this is a choice between those who think this is as good as it gets for Britain and those who think we can do a lot better than this.

576
00:48:35,789 --> 00:48:40,555
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think it's good enough that we've got 700,000 people on zero-hours contracts.

577
00:48:40,575 --> 00:48:42,497
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we can do something about it.

578
00:48:42,477 --> 00:48:45,462
[SPEAKER_07]: And the Prime Minister said earlier that he couldn't live on a zero-hours contract.

579
00:48:45,482 --> 00:48:46,324
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I couldn't either.

580
00:48:46,724 --> 00:48:47,966
[SPEAKER_07]: But let's do something about it.

581
00:48:48,267 --> 00:48:57,443
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's turn this country into a country where if you work month after month, year after year, you don't end up on a zero-hours contract, but you have a legal right to a regular contract.

582
00:48:57,583 --> 00:48:59,647
[SPEAKER_07]: That's just one of the changes that I would make.

583
00:48:59,827 --> 00:49:00,809
[SPEAKER_07]: We can do a lot better than this.

584
00:49:00,829 --> 00:49:01,650
[SPEAKER_07]: We're a great country.

585
00:49:01,630 --> 00:49:04,934
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's whizz through these two straight up.

586
00:49:04,954 --> 00:49:05,435
[SPEAKER_10]: First round of applause.

587
00:49:05,455 --> 00:49:06,757
[SPEAKER_10]: Paula Pearson is next.

588
00:49:06,777 --> 00:49:07,518
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you, Paula?

589
00:49:07,538 --> 00:49:09,340
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question for Mr Miliband?

590
00:49:09,360 --> 00:49:10,101
[SPEAKER_08]: Paula.

591
00:49:10,121 --> 00:49:14,527
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm proud of my working-class background and I'm now a high-rate taxpayer.

592
00:49:15,328 --> 00:49:19,814
[SPEAKER_08]: Labour's messages often leave me feeling demonised and ashamed of earning a good salary.

593
00:49:20,354 --> 00:49:22,177
[SPEAKER_08]: How can I vote for you when you make me feel like this?

594
00:49:23,258 --> 00:49:24,600
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I'm going to try and change...

595
00:49:28,225 --> 00:49:29,567
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me see if I can change your mind.

596
00:49:30,548 --> 00:49:36,215
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, look, I think that the thing that's happening in Britain at the moment is it's the very richest in our society.

597
00:49:36,235 --> 00:49:46,788
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm talking about the top 1% people earning over £150,000 a year who are doing sort of OK. And I think lots and lots of people, including on middle incomes, are finding life really tough.

598
00:49:47,509 --> 00:49:49,371
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, the question is how we do something about it.

599
00:49:50,112 --> 00:49:54,417
[SPEAKER_07]: And I hope you'll get a different message from me tonight if that's the message you've been getting from me.

600
00:49:54,538 --> 00:49:55,579
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me give you an example.

601
00:49:55,939 --> 00:49:57,321
[SPEAKER_07]: Tuition fees.

602
00:49:57,301 --> 00:50:03,929
[SPEAKER_07]: Some people have criticised me for wanting to lower the burden of tuition fees from £9,000 to £6,000 because they say it'll help middle-class families.

603
00:50:04,150 --> 00:50:06,232
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, too right I want to help middle-class families.

604
00:50:06,573 --> 00:50:16,085
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I think lots of families are saying, if my son or daughter is leaving university with £44,000 of debt, that isn't a good situation, let's do something about it with fair changes.

605
00:50:16,165 --> 00:50:21,792
[SPEAKER_07]: So, look, I want a country where you feel you're not struggling, you can get on, and that's one of the changes we'd make.

606
00:50:21,992 --> 00:50:24,996
[SPEAKER_10]: If you're a socialist, does that mean that you're anti-wealth creation?

607
00:50:25,246 --> 00:50:28,852
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I think wealth creation, it says on our party card, democratic socialist.

608
00:50:29,332 --> 00:50:36,624
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that wealth creation is an incredibly important part of building a more prosperous society and a fairer society.

609
00:50:36,844 --> 00:50:46,680
[SPEAKER_07]: But look, the difference with me, Kay, and this is important for the audience, is I think the way we succeed is not simply with those at the top doing well, but all working people succeeding.

610
00:50:46,660 --> 00:50:49,984
[SPEAKER_07]: I say it's when working people succeed that Britain succeeds.

611
00:50:50,004 --> 00:50:51,587
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, that might sound like a political slogan.

612
00:50:51,607 --> 00:50:51,927
[SPEAKER_07]: It isn't.

613
00:50:52,368 --> 00:50:55,171
[SPEAKER_07]: It's actually a reality of the way a country gets on.

614
00:50:55,251 --> 00:51:01,039
[SPEAKER_07]: So, if hard work's rewarded for everyone, not just the bankers with six-figure bonuses, if you get a regular...

615
00:51:01,059 --> 00:51:01,920
[SPEAKER_10]: Sometimes seven-figure bonuses.

616
00:51:01,940 --> 00:51:13,396
[SPEAKER_07]: ..or seven-figure bonuses, if you get regular hours, you know, and you've got some security if you're going out to work and doing the right thing for the country, if you're having an NHS that you can rely on, that's better for the whole country.

617
00:51:13,596 --> 00:51:15,098
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we all benefit from that.

618
00:51:15,078 --> 00:51:16,802
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's bring in Luke Tucker next.

619
00:51:16,842 --> 00:51:17,444
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you, Luke?

620
00:51:17,464 --> 00:51:18,346
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question?

621
00:51:18,366 --> 00:51:19,930
[SPEAKER_10]: You're from Tower Hamlets, I believe.

622
00:51:20,170 --> 00:51:20,331
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

623
00:51:20,571 --> 00:51:21,373
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi, Luke.

624
00:51:21,393 --> 00:51:21,493
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi.

625
00:51:22,315 --> 00:51:28,631
[SPEAKER_02]: If you are Prime Minister after May the 7th, what will the budget deficit be in pounds at the end of five years, and how will you achieve it?

626
00:51:29,453 --> 00:51:32,901
[SPEAKER_07]: So, £75 billion we're going to inherit.

627
00:51:32,881 --> 00:51:39,518
[SPEAKER_07]: We want to balance the books by the end of the Parliament, and we want to cut the deficit every year.

628
00:51:39,578 --> 00:51:41,844
[SPEAKER_07]: And we're going to do it by doing three things.

629
00:51:42,385 --> 00:51:43,889
[SPEAKER_07]: First of all, we'll have fair taxes.

630
00:51:44,330 --> 00:51:50,265
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to reverse the change that David Cameron made, cutting taxes for those earning over £150,000 a year.

631
00:51:50,245 --> 00:51:58,355
[SPEAKER_07]: Secondly, there will have to be spending reductions in areas outside some priorities, like health and education, because we do need to get the deficit down.

632
00:51:58,675 --> 00:52:00,457
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'll make no bones about that to you.

633
00:52:00,477 --> 00:52:01,779
[SPEAKER_07]: That's going to require difficult decisions.

634
00:52:02,139 --> 00:52:05,143
[SPEAKER_07]: But thirdly, really important other thing we've got to do.

635
00:52:05,644 --> 00:52:09,809
[SPEAKER_07]: Why is it that the Conservatives promised to eliminate the deficit and haven't done so?

636
00:52:09,829 --> 00:52:10,870
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's not talk about the Conservatives.

637
00:52:10,890 --> 00:52:11,951
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's talk about what you do.

638
00:52:12,072 --> 00:52:16,557
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sure all our audience remember with Liam Byrne, though, and the note that was left behind.

639
00:52:16,537 --> 00:52:18,199
[SPEAKER_07]: I understand that.

640
00:52:18,219 --> 00:52:19,722
[SPEAKER_07]: I understand that, but I want to draw a lesson.

641
00:52:20,182 --> 00:52:26,652
[SPEAKER_07]: Because the reason why that hasn't happened is because living standards have fallen, so tax revenues have fallen.

642
00:52:27,092 --> 00:52:29,836
[SPEAKER_07]: So the key to getting rid of the deficit is that third element.

643
00:52:30,097 --> 00:52:36,005
[SPEAKER_07]: The tax changes we've announced, the spending reductions, but that key third element of raising living standards.

644
00:52:36,025 --> 00:52:40,792
[SPEAKER_07]: If we raise living standards in this country, we'll also get the tax revenues in and the deficit down.

645
00:52:41,193 --> 00:52:43,136
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's bring in Veronica Monti next.

646
00:52:43,657 --> 00:52:45,379
[SPEAKER_10]: Veronica, what's your question?

647
00:52:45,359 --> 00:53:00,668
[SPEAKER_00]: Why is Labour prepared to deny the people the freedom to choose whether they wish to see their country become a fully-fledged member of the EU?

648
00:53:01,306 --> 00:53:03,108
[SPEAKER_07]: I want us to stay in the EU, Veronica.

649
00:53:03,529 --> 00:53:08,094
[SPEAKER_07]: And as you say, it's not my priority to have a referendum whether we should leave the European Union.

650
00:53:08,114 --> 00:53:08,975
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me explain why.

651
00:53:09,595 --> 00:53:18,726
[SPEAKER_07]: I think when I look at our country, I know what my priorities will be as Prime Minister, to tackle the cost of living crisis, to rescue our NHS, to build a future for our young people.

652
00:53:19,166 --> 00:53:26,254
[SPEAKER_07]: I think leaving the EU will be a disaster for our country because I think we rely on its jobs and the trade we get from being in the EU.

653
00:53:26,735 --> 00:53:28,697
[SPEAKER_07]: I think strategically for Britain,

654
00:53:28,677 --> 00:53:34,442
[SPEAKER_07]: whether you want to tackle terrorism or climate change or a whole range of issues, we've got to be an outward-looking country.

655
00:53:34,903 --> 00:53:36,084
[SPEAKER_07]: And so it's not my priority.

656
00:53:36,424 --> 00:53:44,552
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, I have said, and this is unlikely to happen, but I have said that if there's a transfer of powers from Britain to the EU, a further transfer of powers, we'd have an in-out referendum.

657
00:53:44,652 --> 00:53:45,733
[SPEAKER_07]: But it's not likely to happen.

658
00:53:45,973 --> 00:53:48,876
[SPEAKER_07]: And look, that's what leadership's about, is saying what your priority is.

659
00:53:48,916 --> 00:53:56,423
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't want us to leave the EU, so why would I call a referendum in 2017 and plunge the country into two years of debate about something I don't want to see happen?

660
00:53:56,403 --> 00:54:00,770
[SPEAKER_10]: Just to clarify, if you win the next election, you would not call a referendum in that five-year period?

661
00:54:00,790 --> 00:54:02,052
[SPEAKER_07]: I've said it's unlikely to happen.

662
00:54:02,072 --> 00:54:04,335
[SPEAKER_07]: I've said that the lot for the British people... That's not a definite no.

663
00:54:04,355 --> 00:54:04,816
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it isn't.

664
00:54:04,936 --> 00:54:06,458
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it isn't, because of the criteria I've set.

665
00:54:06,478 --> 00:54:08,101
[SPEAKER_07]: But I'm making no bones about it, Kate.

666
00:54:08,121 --> 00:54:09,142
[SPEAKER_07]: It's very unlikely to happen.

667
00:54:09,223 --> 00:54:13,108
[SPEAKER_07]: OK. Because I've said that if there's a transfer of powers, it will happen, but that doesn't seem likely at the moment.

668
00:54:13,128 --> 00:54:15,392
[SPEAKER_10]: That's a politician's answer, though, isn't it?

669
00:54:15,432 --> 00:54:15,893
[SPEAKER_07]: Not sure.

670
00:54:16,514 --> 00:54:16,934
[SPEAKER_07]: Not sure.

671
00:54:17,816 --> 00:54:19,158
[SPEAKER_10]: Sunil Jagota.

672
00:54:19,178 --> 00:54:19,498
[SPEAKER_10]: Hello, Sunil.

673
00:54:19,518 --> 00:54:20,740
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question?

674
00:54:20,804 --> 00:54:21,626
[SPEAKER_16]: Hi, over here.

675
00:54:22,288 --> 00:54:23,091
[SPEAKER_16]: Oh, hi.

676
00:54:23,111 --> 00:54:23,592
[SPEAKER_16]: Sunil, yeah.

677
00:54:24,134 --> 00:54:27,584
[SPEAKER_16]: Do you not think that your brother would have done a better job?

678
00:54:29,330 --> 00:54:29,430
[SPEAKER_16]: He...

679
00:54:30,136 --> 00:54:31,618
[SPEAKER_16]: Hold on.

680
00:54:31,638 --> 00:54:31,919
[SPEAKER_16]: Hold on.

681
00:54:32,480 --> 00:54:35,825
[SPEAKER_16]: He was better qualified and better positioned.

682
00:54:36,145 --> 00:54:39,270
[SPEAKER_07]: OK. Well, it'll surprise you to know that my answer is no.

683
00:54:41,714 --> 00:54:43,156
[SPEAKER_07]: So, Neil, let me explain why.

684
00:54:43,456 --> 00:54:47,542
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, it was a difficult contest between me and David, and it was a bruising contest.

685
00:54:47,563 --> 00:54:48,304
[SPEAKER_07]: Why did I stand?

686
00:54:48,905 --> 00:54:59,080
[SPEAKER_07]: I thought somebody needed to lead the Labour Party who could move us on from New Labour, because I thought that was the time that was necessary for the country and necessary for our party.

687
00:54:59,060 --> 00:55:02,365
[SPEAKER_07]: And I had strong views about how we needed to change the country.

688
00:55:02,385 --> 00:55:04,588
[SPEAKER_07]: I think this country is too unequal, and we've got to change it.

689
00:55:04,608 --> 00:55:07,052
[SPEAKER_07]: I think New Labour was too relaxed about inequality.

690
00:55:07,292 --> 00:55:09,616
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we made mistakes on foreign policy, like on Iraq.

691
00:55:10,317 --> 00:55:11,719
[SPEAKER_07]: We made mistakes on immigration, too.

692
00:55:11,819 --> 00:55:12,540
[SPEAKER_07]: Maybe we'll come to that.

693
00:55:12,941 --> 00:55:16,025
[SPEAKER_07]: But I thought I was the best person to move the party on.

694
00:55:16,806 --> 00:55:20,972
[SPEAKER_07]: And I stood because that's what I felt was the right thing for the country.

695
00:55:21,033 --> 00:55:23,717
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think I am the right person for the job.

696
00:55:23,997 --> 00:55:26,080
[SPEAKER_07]: I thought it then, and I think it now.

697
00:55:26,414 --> 00:55:31,665
[SPEAKER_10]: I wonder, though, Mr Miliband, what regrets you have about creating such division in your family.

698
00:55:31,705 --> 00:55:32,145
[SPEAKER_07]: It's hard.

699
00:55:33,208 --> 00:55:33,568
[SPEAKER_07]: It's hard.

700
00:55:33,588 --> 00:55:34,570
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll make no bones about it.

701
00:55:34,590 --> 00:55:34,811
[SPEAKER_07]: It's hard.

702
00:55:34,831 --> 00:55:35,552
[SPEAKER_10]: In what way is it hard?

703
00:55:35,813 --> 00:55:36,795
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, because it was bruising.

704
00:55:36,835 --> 00:55:40,622
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, you know, it was bruising for me, it was bruising for David.

705
00:55:41,384 --> 00:55:43,568
[SPEAKER_07]: It's healed, or healing, I would say.

706
00:55:44,130 --> 00:55:47,376
[SPEAKER_07]: Just being completely frank with you about that.

707
00:55:47,356 --> 00:55:48,978
[SPEAKER_10]: So you did fall out?

708
00:55:49,759 --> 00:55:52,982
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, we had a very difficult contest, so it was very difficult.

709
00:55:53,002 --> 00:55:53,723
[SPEAKER_07]: Did you not talk?

710
00:55:54,003 --> 00:55:57,988
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it wasn't that we didn't talk, but I would say it was strained, not surprisingly.

711
00:55:58,448 --> 00:56:01,331
[SPEAKER_07]: But look, I care deeply about this country.

712
00:56:02,332 --> 00:56:06,977
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe I'm the right person to be Prime Minister, and I thought it when I stood in 2010.

713
00:56:07,138 --> 00:56:14,005
[SPEAKER_07]: I wouldn't have gone through all of that if I didn't have pretty strong convictions about how we need to change Britain.

714
00:56:14,356 --> 00:56:16,860
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, she's a pretty hardy soul.

715
00:56:17,281 --> 00:56:18,283
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm glad to hear it.

716
00:56:18,583 --> 00:56:20,407
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's bring in Lynne Gaff now, should we?

717
00:56:20,427 --> 00:56:21,168
[SPEAKER_10]: Hello to you, Lynne.

718
00:56:21,188 --> 00:56:24,053
[SPEAKER_10]: What's your question this evening for us?

719
00:56:24,073 --> 00:56:24,834
[SPEAKER_10]: Just in the middle there.

720
00:56:25,175 --> 00:56:25,395
[SPEAKER_13]: Lynne.

721
00:56:25,796 --> 00:56:31,386
[SPEAKER_13]: Mr Miliband, do you think socialism remains an important and evident Labour Party value?

722
00:56:32,167 --> 00:56:33,850
[SPEAKER_13]: If so, why and how?

723
00:56:34,994 --> 00:56:38,299
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I call it democratic socialism, that's what's on our party card, Lyn.

724
00:56:39,260 --> 00:56:44,247
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes is the answer, because I think, I believe in a fairer, more equal society.

725
00:56:44,928 --> 00:56:50,697
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, each generation of Labour politicians puts it into practice in their own generation.

726
00:56:51,177 --> 00:56:52,179
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, what does it mean today?

727
00:56:52,199 --> 00:56:54,522
[SPEAKER_07]: And it goes back to the question that this lady asked.

728
00:56:54,502 --> 00:56:56,405
[SPEAKER_07]: which is what I see in Britain.

729
00:56:56,786 --> 00:56:59,470
[SPEAKER_07]: And you know, this is the thing that countries all around the world are grappling with.

730
00:56:59,490 --> 00:57:00,992
[SPEAKER_07]: This is a central question we face.

731
00:57:01,713 --> 00:57:04,738
[SPEAKER_07]: Are we going to be countries that work for the richest and most powerful?

732
00:57:04,758 --> 00:57:06,922
[SPEAKER_07]: This is what America is facing, President Obama as well.

733
00:57:07,322 --> 00:57:12,190
[SPEAKER_07]: Are we going to be a country that just works for the richest and most powerful, or is everyone going to get a fair shot?

734
00:57:12,170 --> 00:57:14,433
[SPEAKER_07]: Is everyone going to play by the same rules?

735
00:57:15,354 --> 00:57:19,678
[SPEAKER_07]: If you're going to do the right thing, go out to work, are you going to be able to build a life for you and yourself and your family?

736
00:57:19,999 --> 00:57:21,741
[SPEAKER_07]: Lots of people are doubting that in Britain.

737
00:57:21,921 --> 00:57:27,507
[SPEAKER_07]: To the gentleman who asked me whether I was too gloomy, that's why I think it sometimes might sound that way.

738
00:57:27,747 --> 00:57:32,012
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I think people are asking, hang on a minute, this country was supposed to work for me.

739
00:57:32,032 --> 00:57:33,294
[SPEAKER_07]: Why doesn't it work for me anymore?

740
00:57:33,494 --> 00:57:35,036
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm doing what everyone tells me I should do.

741
00:57:35,556 --> 00:57:41,603
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's what democratic socialism means, a fairer, more equal society, making this country work for working people again.

742
00:57:41,583 --> 00:57:42,224
[SPEAKER_13]: What do you think, Lyn?

743
00:57:43,285 --> 00:57:46,990
[SPEAKER_13]: I think that they need to be revisited, those values within the Labour Party currently.

744
00:57:47,230 --> 00:57:47,331
[SPEAKER_13]: OK.

745
00:57:47,451 --> 00:57:48,472
[SPEAKER_13]: It needs to be reaffirmed.

746
00:57:49,113 --> 00:57:52,538
[SPEAKER_10]: We thought that it would... You've got your hand up there just here in the second row.

747
00:57:52,558 --> 00:57:54,640
[SPEAKER_10]: You just wanted to ask a quick follow-up question.

748
00:57:54,660 --> 00:57:55,121
[SPEAKER_06]: What's your name?

749
00:57:55,241 --> 00:57:56,463
[SPEAKER_10]: Can you just wait for the microphone?

750
00:57:56,483 --> 00:57:57,324
[SPEAKER_10]: There we go, you've got it now.

751
00:57:57,624 --> 00:57:58,385
[SPEAKER_06]: What's your name?

752
00:57:58,525 --> 00:57:58,806
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry.

753
00:57:58,906 --> 00:57:59,467
[SPEAKER_06]: Harry, hi.

754
00:57:59,487 --> 00:58:03,913
[SPEAKER_06]: How are you going to be different from Nick Clegg and their broken promises, or David Cameron and his broken promises?

755
00:58:04,073 --> 00:58:07,978
[SPEAKER_06]: Are you just going to sit here and sugarcoat things and sweeten things up so we can vote for you?

756
00:58:07,958 --> 00:58:08,238
[SPEAKER_07]: No.

757
00:58:08,399 --> 00:58:11,683
[SPEAKER_06]: Or are you actually going to give us some security and actually follow through on your promises?

758
00:58:11,763 --> 00:58:13,405
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I'm going to follow through on my promises.

759
00:58:13,425 --> 00:58:15,007
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, look, all politicians say that.

760
00:58:15,027 --> 00:58:17,630
[SPEAKER_07]: You're going to have to make a judgment tonight about whether I'm going to do it.

761
00:58:17,650 --> 00:58:21,015
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me give you a very specific example that goes back to this point about tuition fees.

762
00:58:21,535 --> 00:58:26,802
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, in 2011, I said I wanted to cut the tuition fee to £6,000, right?

763
00:58:27,603 --> 00:58:32,970
[SPEAKER_07]: And then as the Parliament wore on, some people said, ah, Miliband's going to break his promise just like Clegg did.

764
00:58:33,254 --> 00:58:38,241
[SPEAKER_07]: And you know, it's the right thing to do to cut tuition fees to 6,000 pounds, and I'm going to do it, and I've shown how I'll pay for it.

765
00:58:38,902 --> 00:58:41,926
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm doing it because it's the right thing to do, but I'm also doing it for another reason.

766
00:58:41,946 --> 00:58:44,730
[SPEAKER_07]: Because trust in politics is so important.

767
00:58:44,750 --> 00:58:46,332
[SPEAKER_07]: It's so important we rebuild trust.

768
00:58:46,352 --> 00:58:53,102
[SPEAKER_07]: I sometimes say, Harry, I want to be the first politician to under-promise and over-deliver, not over-promise and under-deliver.

769
00:58:53,382 --> 00:58:57,468
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, I'll come back in five years if I'm prime minister, and you tell me whether I've achieved it or not.

770
00:58:57,868 --> 00:59:00,612
[SPEAKER_07]: But I've tried to set out some promises that I know I can keep.

771
00:59:00,743 --> 00:59:03,949
[SPEAKER_10]: interesting to think what politicians think about each other.

772
00:59:04,009 --> 00:59:11,763
[SPEAKER_10]: You will remember perhaps we asked Matthew Brown in the first half of our town hall debate, so it is only fair to put the same question to you.

773
00:59:11,804 --> 00:59:20,119
[SPEAKER_10]: What do you think are David Cameron's best qualities, given that you have previously called him a chicken and a bully?

774
00:59:21,382 --> 00:59:26,238
[SPEAKER_07]: I'd say two things about what David Cameron has achieved as Prime Minister, which I admire.

775
00:59:26,760 --> 00:59:28,626
[SPEAKER_07]: The first is his commitment to equal marriage.

776
00:59:29,188 --> 00:59:30,412
[SPEAKER_07]: It was hard in his party.

777
00:59:31,135 --> 00:59:32,961
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the right thing to do for the country.

778
00:59:34,966 --> 00:59:41,396
[SPEAKER_07]: And second, and this isn't going to be universally popular, his commitment on overseas development, a 0.7%.

779
00:59:41,617 --> 00:59:53,296
[SPEAKER_07]: And now, there'll be some people who don't like me saying that, but he took a risk in the Conservative Party by saying this is the right thing to do, and he's kept to that, and I think it's right that he did.

780
00:59:53,696 --> 00:59:55,139
[SPEAKER_10]: So you think he's a decent enough bloke then?

781
00:59:55,179 --> 00:59:56,080
[SPEAKER_10]: Would you have a pint with him?

782
00:59:56,836 --> 00:59:58,098
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know whether we'd have a pint.

783
00:59:59,920 --> 01:00:01,122
[SPEAKER_07]: It's hard.

784
01:00:01,683 --> 01:00:07,651
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, it's hard when we share a bacon sandwich or something.

785
01:00:08,111 --> 01:00:15,201
[SPEAKER_07]: No, look, it's hard when you're in politics because you see me and him shouting at each other at Prime Minister's questions, and it's not very edifying.

786
01:00:16,202 --> 01:00:18,085
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's be honest, it's not a great advert for politics.

787
01:00:18,105 --> 01:00:21,730
[SPEAKER_07]: But as he said earlier, it's hard to avoid the back and forth.

788
01:00:22,098 --> 01:00:26,044
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's bring in Geoffrey Louis Reid, just here at the front.

789
01:00:26,645 --> 01:00:27,286
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are you, Geoffrey?

790
01:00:27,306 --> 01:00:27,506
[SPEAKER_10]: Just here.

791
01:00:28,167 --> 01:00:29,449
[SPEAKER_01]: Ed, my question to you is this.

792
01:00:30,210 --> 01:00:34,517
[SPEAKER_01]: You've made it quite difficult for your supporters and for people that are undecided.

793
01:00:34,537 --> 01:00:36,500
[SPEAKER_01]: OK. That's not a great start.

794
01:00:36,520 --> 01:00:47,937
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, the reason is that you've had a few gaffes recently and you don't really seem to be fighting for the values that your party stands for.

795
01:00:48,018 --> 01:00:48,820
[SPEAKER_01]: OK.

796
01:00:48,920 --> 01:00:59,606
[SPEAKER_01]: Meaning, you know, places like Cressingham Gardens, which is the Labour council in Lambeth, or museum closures because of the decimation of arts budgets, and austerity in general.

797
01:00:59,867 --> 01:01:03,816
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, Geoffrey, first of all, austerity

798
01:01:03,796 --> 01:01:10,363
[SPEAKER_07]: Tory austerity is happening, and the cuts you're talking about in the councils are happening because of the Conservative government's decisions.

799
01:01:10,683 --> 01:01:13,346
[SPEAKER_07]: Our spending plans are very different from theirs for the future.

800
01:01:13,586 --> 01:01:17,150
[SPEAKER_07]: They want cuts bigger in the next three years than the last five.

801
01:01:17,170 --> 01:01:21,195
[SPEAKER_07]: But let me go to the other point, which I think is implicit in your question about GAFs, so-called, right?

802
01:01:21,975 --> 01:01:24,879
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not going to win a contest for who looks best eating a bacon sandwich.

803
01:01:24,899 --> 01:01:28,082
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we can all agree about that.

804
01:01:28,062 --> 01:01:30,064
[SPEAKER_10]: It's not happy with your answer.

805
01:01:30,084 --> 01:01:31,946
[SPEAKER_10]: They're shaking heads and all sorts of things.

806
01:01:31,966 --> 01:01:33,288
[SPEAKER_07]: Can we get a microphone there, sir?

807
01:01:33,368 --> 01:01:34,389
[SPEAKER_07]: Can I just make this one point?

808
01:01:34,930 --> 01:01:36,452
[SPEAKER_07]: Very quickly, if you would.

809
01:01:36,472 --> 01:01:47,384
[SPEAKER_07]: What I stand for, what I think matters in politics, is ideas to change the country, principles, sticking to your principles when you've got powerful opponents like the energy companies or the banks or Rupert Murdoch, and frankly, decency.

810
01:01:48,245 --> 01:01:50,568
[SPEAKER_07]: Reaching out to people who are the most vulnerable in our society.

811
01:01:50,588 --> 01:01:52,550
[SPEAKER_10]: OK. Sir, what did you want to come back with?

812
01:01:52,730 --> 01:01:53,631
[SPEAKER_10]: My question is,

813
01:01:53,864 --> 01:01:58,449
[SPEAKER_03]: Everyone in this country remembers 13 years of a Labour government under Blair and Brown, OK?

814
01:01:58,469 --> 01:02:11,001
[SPEAKER_03]: And you talk about austerity to us, but the reason there's austerity is because all the money was spent, everything was thrown away, nothing was planned for a rainy day, and all I hear is, is you say, well, it was a global economy and it was a global crisis.

815
01:02:11,042 --> 01:02:14,505
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, but the liberalisation of the banks and everything came from your party.

816
01:02:14,805 --> 01:02:21,812
[SPEAKER_03]: And what I want to know, what I want to know is, if people are going to vote Labour, can you promise us that you've learnt from the mistakes that led to the mess that we're now in?

817
01:02:22,033 --> 01:02:23,314
[SPEAKER_03]: What's your name, sir?

818
01:02:23,935 --> 01:02:29,649
[SPEAKER_07]: Tim, let me be very specific on that, Tim.

819
01:02:29,729 --> 01:02:31,077
[SPEAKER_07]: We were wrong.

820
01:02:31,546 --> 01:02:32,227
[SPEAKER_17]: Sorry?

821
01:02:32,287 --> 01:02:32,768
[SPEAKER_07]: Dean.

822
01:02:32,788 --> 01:02:33,770
[SPEAKER_07]: Dean, sorry.

823
01:02:33,810 --> 01:02:35,612
[SPEAKER_07]: We were wrong on the regulation of the banks.

824
01:02:35,893 --> 01:02:36,494
[SPEAKER_07]: We got it wrong.

825
01:02:36,814 --> 01:02:38,717
[SPEAKER_07]: The banks were under-regulated, right?

826
01:02:39,018 --> 01:02:45,248
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, other people were saying we should regulate them even less, but we were wrong, along with countries all round the world and regulators around the world.

827
01:02:45,288 --> 01:02:46,269
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm sorry we got it wrong.

828
01:02:47,070 --> 01:02:52,599
[SPEAKER_07]: OK. And we've got to learn from that, and I believe I have learnt from that in my five years as leader of the opposition.

829
01:02:52,739 --> 01:02:53,781
[SPEAKER_07]: But has Ed Balls?

830
01:02:54,162 --> 01:02:56,826
[SPEAKER_07]: He absolutely has.

831
01:02:56,846 --> 01:02:57,587
[SPEAKER_16]: Because I don't understand how you...

832
01:02:57,989 --> 01:03:03,655
[SPEAKER_07]: He was the first person to say we've got to make sure that the banks are properly regulated in the future.

833
01:03:03,675 --> 01:03:04,516
[SPEAKER_07]: But let me say something else.

834
01:03:04,756 --> 01:03:06,518
[SPEAKER_07]: The banks have got to work better for our businesses.

835
01:03:06,818 --> 01:03:11,162
[SPEAKER_07]: That is a problem that goes back decades, these historic problems that we've got to solve.

836
01:03:11,182 --> 01:03:13,585
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let me just put the final question from Andy Palmer.

837
01:03:13,645 --> 01:03:19,431
[SPEAKER_10]: Andy's saying, why is Labour only neck and neck with the Conservatives in the opinion polls after five years of opposition?

838
01:03:19,451 --> 01:03:24,436
[SPEAKER_10]: Sky News poll of polls today, 279 seats for you, 278 for the Conservatives.

839
01:03:24,676 --> 01:03:26,778
[SPEAKER_10]: You should be steaming ahead and you're not.

840
01:03:26,878 --> 01:03:27,439
[SPEAKER_10]: Why?

841
01:03:28,263 --> 01:03:32,489
[SPEAKER_07]: I take an old-fashioned view on this, which is, let's let the people decide in six weeks' time, Kay.

842
01:03:32,729 --> 01:03:33,651
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not a commentator.

843
01:03:34,131 --> 01:03:36,375
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, we were coming out of government in 2010.

844
01:03:36,515 --> 01:03:39,659
[SPEAKER_07]: It's hard when you're having to be a one-term opposition.

845
01:03:39,820 --> 01:03:43,765
[SPEAKER_07]: But the thing I'm interested in is this big battle about the future of the country and the people are the boss.

846
01:03:44,246 --> 01:03:46,189
[SPEAKER_07]: And let's see what they decide on May the 7th.

847
01:03:46,689 --> 01:03:47,691
[SPEAKER_10]: Would you believe we're out of time?

848
01:03:48,552 --> 01:03:49,173
[SPEAKER_07]: We're out of time.

849
01:03:49,213 --> 01:03:49,574
[SPEAKER_10]: Already?

850
01:03:49,634 --> 01:03:49,974
[SPEAKER_10]: Already.

851
01:03:50,495 --> 01:03:50,895
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, my goodness.

852
01:03:50,916 --> 01:03:51,857
[SPEAKER_10]: 18 minutes gone.

853
01:03:52,017 --> 01:03:53,920
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much indeed for joining us, Mr Maloney.

854
01:03:53,940 --> 01:03:54,160
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

855
01:03:54,180 --> 01:03:56,003
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you all very much.

856
01:03:56,023 --> 01:03:56,143
[SPEAKER_10]: Enjoy.

857
01:04:00,747 --> 01:04:03,936
[SPEAKER_10]: He's not finished just yet, though.

858
01:04:03,956 --> 01:04:07,084
[SPEAKER_10]: Coming next, it's another band's head-to-head with Jeremy Paxman.

859
01:04:07,104 --> 01:04:08,267
[SPEAKER_10]: That's going to be worth watching.

860
01:04:08,287 --> 01:04:14,183
[SPEAKER_10]: Stay tuned.

861
01:08:26,039 --> 01:08:29,608
[SPEAKER_05]: This is Cameron and Miliband live, the battle for number 10.

862
01:08:29,668 --> 01:08:32,595
[SPEAKER_05]: With me now is the Labour leader, Ed Miliband.

863
01:08:33,096 --> 01:08:38,108
[SPEAKER_05]: Ed Miliband, do you think Britain is full... ..in terms of immigration?

864
01:08:38,269 --> 01:08:39,171
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

865
01:08:39,623 --> 01:08:41,024
[SPEAKER_07]: I wouldn't describe it that way, no.

866
01:08:41,885 --> 01:08:44,668
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we've got very high levels of migration.

867
01:08:45,509 --> 01:08:50,694
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that we do need to try and get those levels of migration down, particularly low-skilled migration.

868
01:08:50,715 --> 01:08:51,595
[SPEAKER_05]: Because they're too high now.

869
01:08:51,816 --> 01:08:53,938
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, but I'll tell you one thing, very important.

870
01:08:54,058 --> 01:08:59,984
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not going to make a false promise on this, because, look, David Cameron did make that promise on tens of thousands of net migration.

871
01:09:00,004 --> 01:09:02,887
[SPEAKER_05]: You've got form on false promises on immigration, haven't you?

872
01:09:03,067 --> 01:09:03,628
[SPEAKER_05]: Me, personally.

873
01:09:04,128 --> 01:09:05,910
[SPEAKER_05]: Your government, your party.

874
01:09:05,930 --> 01:09:06,631
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, we got it wrong.

875
01:09:06,771 --> 01:09:07,812
[SPEAKER_05]: You got it completely wrong.

876
01:09:07,832 --> 01:09:08,533
[SPEAKER_05]: We got it wrong, yeah.

877
01:09:08,513 --> 01:09:10,676
[SPEAKER_05]: Your figures were farcical.

878
01:09:10,877 --> 01:09:11,417
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, they were wrong.

879
01:09:12,159 --> 01:09:12,259
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

880
01:09:12,279 --> 01:09:14,202
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me say two things, though, about this, which are important.

881
01:09:14,242 --> 01:09:17,326
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, you said... Let me just make a point about immigration, because you asked me a question.

882
01:09:17,346 --> 01:09:17,927
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me answer it.

883
01:09:18,728 --> 01:09:22,154
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, I think that we benefit from our diversity.

884
01:09:22,895 --> 01:09:27,101
[SPEAKER_07]: Immigrants over the years have made a big contribution to our country, but we do need proper controls.

885
01:09:27,141 --> 01:09:28,844
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me just say this, Jeremy.

886
01:09:28,924 --> 01:09:34,993
[SPEAKER_07]: A Labour government would say that if people come here, they can't get benefits for the first two years, and we will do something else.

887
01:09:34,973 --> 01:09:36,795
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm not talking about benefits.

888
01:09:36,815 --> 01:09:37,956
[SPEAKER_05]: But you're talking about immigration.

889
01:09:38,076 --> 01:09:39,598
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm talking about numbers.

890
01:09:39,978 --> 01:09:40,199
[SPEAKER_07]: Right.

891
01:09:40,359 --> 01:09:48,407
[SPEAKER_05]: And let me tell you, the way we all... Supposing we got to a figure of 70 million in 10 or 15 years' population in this country, is that acceptable?

892
01:09:48,748 --> 01:09:50,069
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm not going to get into your hypotheticals.

893
01:09:50,089 --> 01:09:52,812
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me say, I think we can get low-skill migration down.

894
01:09:53,233 --> 01:09:53,933
[SPEAKER_07]: So...

895
01:09:53,953 --> 01:09:55,115
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not going to start speculating about numbers.

896
01:09:55,135 --> 01:09:55,815
[SPEAKER_05]: No number is too great.

897
01:09:55,976 --> 01:09:56,937
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I'm not saying that.

898
01:09:56,957 --> 01:09:58,018
[SPEAKER_07]: 75 million?

899
01:09:58,218 --> 01:09:58,919
[SPEAKER_07]: 80 million?

900
01:09:58,939 --> 01:09:59,379
[SPEAKER_07]: Come on.

901
01:09:59,419 --> 01:10:00,000
[SPEAKER_07]: 95 million?

902
01:10:00,140 --> 01:10:00,981
[SPEAKER_07]: 100 million?

903
01:10:01,282 --> 01:10:02,484
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me say what I'm going to do.

904
01:10:02,744 --> 01:10:06,028
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me say what I'm going to do, because that's what matters, rather than speculating about figures.

905
01:10:06,449 --> 01:10:08,151
[SPEAKER_07]: I want to get low-skill migration down.

906
01:10:08,572 --> 01:10:22,029
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think the controls we're talking about, not just on benefits, but on stopping the undercutting of wages, because people are being brought into the country to undermine the minimum wage and various other things, I think they will help to get low-skill migration down.

907
01:10:22,210 --> 01:10:27,036
[SPEAKER_07]: But if what you're saying to me is, would it be better for our country, for example, to withdraw from the European Union?

908
01:10:27,016 --> 01:10:28,958
[SPEAKER_05]: I've mentioned the European Union.

909
01:10:28,978 --> 01:10:30,560
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I'll tell you why I'm saying this.

910
01:10:30,581 --> 01:10:32,543
[SPEAKER_07]: You're making up a question to yourself.

911
01:10:33,244 --> 01:10:33,584
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not.

912
01:10:34,305 --> 01:10:36,288
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm saying there's a big choice at this election, Jeremy.

913
01:10:36,308 --> 01:10:37,589
[SPEAKER_07]: There is a choice at this election.

914
01:10:38,130 --> 01:10:45,720
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe that we can bring in controls on migration, sensible controls, but I'm not going to make false promises or put forward false solutions either.

915
01:10:46,120 --> 01:10:51,507
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm just asking you if you think there's any natural limit to the population of this country.

916
01:10:51,948 --> 01:10:54,431
[SPEAKER_05]: And I'm not going to get drawn into a speculation about a number.

917
01:10:54,491 --> 01:10:56,213
[SPEAKER_05]: You don't think there is a natural limit?

918
01:10:56,193 --> 01:11:00,724
[SPEAKER_07]: No, of course there are limits, but the limits are expressed... Oh, what, are you keeping them to yourself?

919
01:11:00,744 --> 01:11:06,899
[SPEAKER_07]: The limits are expressed in the decisions you take year by year, and I've explained some of the decisions that we will make.

920
01:11:07,962 --> 01:11:13,375
[SPEAKER_05]: So, as it seems to you now, there is no figure that you're willing to share with the public.

921
01:11:13,642 --> 01:11:16,326
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not going to pluck a figure out of the air about the correct level.

922
01:11:16,386 --> 01:11:17,808
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, I assume you've thought about it.

923
01:11:18,109 --> 01:11:20,653
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I've thought about the right thing to do on migration.

924
01:11:21,033 --> 01:11:22,876
[SPEAKER_07]: And we need to have controls on migration.

925
01:11:23,016 --> 01:11:25,941
[SPEAKER_07]: And I've explained some of those controls, but I'm not going to pluck a figure out of the air.

926
01:11:25,981 --> 01:11:27,263
[SPEAKER_05]: There's no finite limit.

927
01:11:27,283 --> 01:11:35,295
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, you've already conceded that when your party was last in government, it got immigration completely wrong.

928
01:11:35,415 --> 01:11:35,515
Sure.

929
01:11:36,237 --> 01:11:48,712
[SPEAKER_05]: You were predicting figures of between 5,000 and 13,000 immigrants a year from the expansion of the EU in 2004, and actually something like 400,000 people came in.

930
01:11:49,433 --> 01:11:52,197
[SPEAKER_05]: That's the entire population of Malta equivalent.

931
01:11:54,479 --> 01:11:57,503
[SPEAKER_05]: What else did that government do wrong when you were last in power?

932
01:11:58,259 --> 01:12:04,210
[SPEAKER_07]: I think there's two things that I would mention in addition to that.

933
01:12:04,911 --> 01:12:07,656
[SPEAKER_07]: By the way, I'm proud of many of the things we did, but two things I would mention.

934
01:12:07,976 --> 01:12:10,701
[SPEAKER_07]: First of all, I think we were too relaxed about inequality.

935
01:12:11,643 --> 01:12:16,111
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that the gap got bigger and I think lots of people fell behind.

936
01:12:16,351 --> 01:12:17,533
[SPEAKER_07]: Did you borrow too much?

937
01:12:18,408 --> 01:12:23,844
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that the global financial crisis, I think the global financial crisis is what drove borrowing up.

938
01:12:23,864 --> 01:12:25,228
[SPEAKER_05]: Did you borrow too much?

939
01:12:25,248 --> 01:12:28,598
[SPEAKER_07]: The figure was too high by the end of our time in government as a result of the global financial crisis.

940
01:12:28,618 --> 01:12:29,220
[SPEAKER_05]: So you did borrow too much?

941
01:12:29,521 --> 01:12:32,249
[SPEAKER_07]: Well I'm saying the figure was too high as a result of the global financial crisis.

942
01:12:32,269 --> 01:12:33,312
[SPEAKER_07]: Did you spend too much?

943
01:12:33,713 --> 01:12:40,222
[SPEAKER_07]: I think there were spending programmes that maybe weren't as good as they could have been, but I don't believe, no.

944
01:12:40,943 --> 01:12:42,465
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't believe, no.

945
01:12:42,485 --> 01:12:43,426
[SPEAKER_07]: Give us a clue, come on.

946
01:12:43,446 --> 01:12:44,347
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it's an important point.

947
01:12:44,768 --> 01:12:47,151
[SPEAKER_07]: Which ones weren't quite as good as they should have been?

948
01:12:47,171 --> 01:12:48,573
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, it's an important point.

949
01:12:48,633 --> 01:12:50,055
[SPEAKER_07]: No government gets it completely right.

950
01:12:50,075 --> 01:12:50,836
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a very important point.

951
01:12:50,876 --> 01:12:52,718
[SPEAKER_07]: That's why it's important to have some detail.

952
01:12:52,698 --> 01:13:01,836
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me just say, I think the overall point was the financial crisis caused by overspending by Labour.

953
01:13:01,916 --> 01:13:02,758
[SPEAKER_07]: No, the answer is no.

954
01:13:02,998 --> 01:13:07,146
[SPEAKER_05]: I think investment in health and education... You're asking yourself a question I haven't asked you.

955
01:13:08,020 --> 01:13:10,364
[SPEAKER_05]: My question was, did you borrow too much?

956
01:13:10,965 --> 01:13:12,988
[SPEAKER_05]: You think, no, you didn't borrow too much.

957
01:13:13,248 --> 01:13:14,370
[SPEAKER_05]: Did you spend too much?

958
01:13:14,911 --> 01:13:16,013
[SPEAKER_05]: Some programmes perhaps.

959
01:13:16,033 --> 01:13:17,315
[SPEAKER_05]: Now you're asking yourself questions.

960
01:13:17,335 --> 01:13:23,565
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, I'm trying to summarise your position according to the questions you've been asked rather than the questions you've asked yourself.

961
01:13:24,997 --> 01:13:30,485
[SPEAKER_07]: What I would say is, for example, the Dome was not a good example of the way money is spent.

962
01:13:30,705 --> 01:13:32,148
[SPEAKER_07]: Governments make mistakes.

963
01:13:32,448 --> 01:13:34,030
[SPEAKER_07]: Governments make mistakes.

964
01:13:34,050 --> 01:13:35,693
[SPEAKER_07]: There are always inefficiencies in government.

965
01:13:35,733 --> 01:13:36,975
[SPEAKER_07]: Of course there are inefficiencies.

966
01:13:37,175 --> 01:13:40,099
[SPEAKER_07]: Probably too many reorganisations of public services, which waste money.

967
01:13:40,179 --> 01:13:41,061
[SPEAKER_07]: Of course that's right.

968
01:13:41,321 --> 01:13:43,404
[SPEAKER_07]: But I'm talking about the overall picture, Jeremy.

969
01:13:43,424 --> 01:13:46,188
[SPEAKER_07]: But the other thing I'd say to you is, look, let's talk about the future.

970
01:13:46,469 --> 01:13:47,410
[SPEAKER_05]: Because there's a big...

971
01:13:47,390 --> 01:13:57,290
[SPEAKER_05]: Right, OK. Let's talk about the future, because virtually every single one of your forecasts on the future of the economy during this present government has been wrong, hasn't it?

972
01:13:57,731 --> 01:14:01,698
[SPEAKER_05]: You forecast that unemployment would rise, you forecast that wages would fall.

973
01:14:01,999 --> 01:14:04,624
[SPEAKER_05]: At one point, I think, you even forecast that inflation would rise.

974
01:14:04,664 --> 01:14:05,786
[SPEAKER_05]: Inflation's now at zero.

975
01:14:06,067 --> 01:14:07,069
[SPEAKER_05]: Wages have fallen.

976
01:14:07,454 --> 01:14:11,482
[SPEAKER_07]: People are £1,600 a year worse off than they were when this government came to power.

977
01:14:11,642 --> 01:14:13,967
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the worst record on living standards since the 1920s.

978
01:14:14,187 --> 01:14:15,771
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is the argument of this election.

979
01:14:15,991 --> 01:14:18,636
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, David Cameron wants to say... Do you want to say unemployment has fallen?

980
01:14:18,656 --> 01:14:19,137
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, hang on a minute.

981
01:14:19,157 --> 01:14:19,999
[SPEAKER_07]: You asked about wages.

982
01:14:20,039 --> 01:14:21,582
[SPEAKER_07]: You said I was wrong that wages had fallen.

983
01:14:21,602 --> 01:14:22,965
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I said four costs were wrong.

984
01:14:22,945 --> 01:14:25,488
[SPEAKER_07]: No, you said that I forecast that wages would fall, Jeremy.

985
01:14:25,508 --> 01:14:25,728
[SPEAKER_07]: You did.

986
01:14:25,748 --> 01:14:26,409
[SPEAKER_07]: And they did, yes.

987
01:14:26,469 --> 01:14:27,430
[SPEAKER_07]: And I was right, right?

988
01:14:27,730 --> 01:14:28,551
[SPEAKER_07]: They did fall.

989
01:14:28,571 --> 01:14:28,872
[SPEAKER_07]: They did fall.

990
01:14:28,892 --> 01:14:30,573
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, you're also claiming to be right on unemployment.

991
01:14:30,593 --> 01:14:31,795
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, you asked me about wages.

992
01:14:32,075 --> 01:14:33,036
[SPEAKER_05]: I didn't ask you three things.

993
01:14:33,076 --> 01:14:33,877
[SPEAKER_05]: I mentioned three things.

994
01:14:34,057 --> 01:14:37,481
[SPEAKER_07]: Unemployment, I mentioned wage levels, and I mentioned inflation.

995
01:14:37,501 --> 01:14:41,065
[SPEAKER_07]: On unemployment, I was quoting the Office of Budget Responsibility forecast.

996
01:14:41,085 --> 01:14:43,908
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, as it turned out, that forecast turned out to be wrong.

997
01:14:44,108 --> 01:14:45,850
[SPEAKER_07]: But look, let's go to the big picture here.

998
01:14:45,890 --> 01:14:48,413
[SPEAKER_07]: The big picture is of this election.

999
01:14:48,393 --> 01:14:49,715
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we think the economy is fixed?

1000
01:14:49,735 --> 01:14:50,937
[SPEAKER_07]: David Cameron was on earlier.

1001
01:14:51,197 --> 01:14:52,479
[SPEAKER_07]: He says things are good, right?

1002
01:14:52,719 --> 01:14:53,420
[SPEAKER_07]: And things are fine.

1003
01:14:53,761 --> 01:14:57,026
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think things are fine for the reasons that I set out in the town meeting earlier on.

1004
01:14:57,306 --> 01:15:00,791
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I think we are too much based on low wages.

1005
01:15:01,252 --> 01:15:03,015
[SPEAKER_07]: I think work is too insecure.

1006
01:15:03,355 --> 01:15:07,241
[SPEAKER_07]: I think our young people are burdened down by a lack of opportunity.

1007
01:15:07,261 --> 01:15:09,083
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is what's got to change about the country.

1008
01:15:09,644 --> 01:15:10,806
[SPEAKER_07]: What would you cut?

1009
01:15:11,984 --> 01:15:13,286
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, let me explain.

1010
01:15:13,786 --> 01:15:19,553
[SPEAKER_07]: We've said outside areas like education and health, key protected areas, there are going to be reductions in spending.

1011
01:15:19,834 --> 01:15:27,083
[SPEAKER_07]: And we've set out some of those cuts, like the winter fuel allowance for pensioners with incomes over £42,000 a year.

1012
01:15:27,563 --> 01:15:33,971
[SPEAKER_07]: We've talked about the ways in which we will cut money through efficiencies in the police, in local government.

1013
01:15:34,432 --> 01:15:37,236
[SPEAKER_07]: We've said, for example, that child benefit will be restricted to 1%.

1014
01:15:38,037 --> 01:15:40,860
[SPEAKER_07]: We said we'll reverse the... What does that come to?

1015
01:15:40,840 --> 01:15:44,965
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, the figure is at least hundreds of millions, more than a billion pounds.

1016
01:15:44,985 --> 01:15:45,525
[SPEAKER_07]: Hundreds of millions.

1017
01:15:45,846 --> 01:15:47,267
[SPEAKER_07]: But look, that's not the point.

1018
01:15:47,347 --> 01:15:48,248
[SPEAKER_07]: Because let me explain.

1019
01:15:48,869 --> 01:15:52,273
[SPEAKER_07]: We're going to have to make these decisions when we're in government.

1020
01:15:52,293 --> 01:15:54,896
[SPEAKER_07]: But I've got to set out an overall approach.

1021
01:15:55,316 --> 01:15:57,058
[SPEAKER_07]: And I have set out an overall approach.

1022
01:15:57,399 --> 01:16:01,103
[SPEAKER_07]: I've set out an overall approach which says, as I said earlier, it's about fair taxes.

1023
01:16:01,643 --> 01:16:07,690
[SPEAKER_07]: It's about, I'm a Labour leader going into the election saying we're going to reduce spending outside a small minority of areas.

1024
01:16:07,890 --> 01:16:10,273
[SPEAKER_07]: Tony Blair never went into an election saying that.

1025
01:16:11,198 --> 01:16:13,904
[SPEAKER_07]: What Tony Blair did is Tony Blair's affair, isn't it?

1026
01:16:14,565 --> 01:16:17,652
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it's a point about my approach, Jeremy.

1027
01:16:17,732 --> 01:16:18,955
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not denying the need.

1028
01:16:19,156 --> 01:16:20,238
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not denying the need.

1029
01:16:20,258 --> 01:16:21,922
[SPEAKER_07]: Would overall spending be greater?

1030
01:16:22,603 --> 01:16:24,347
[SPEAKER_07]: No, it would fall.

1031
01:16:24,530 --> 01:16:26,393
[SPEAKER_07]: You would spend less than the Tories.

1032
01:16:26,413 --> 01:16:27,935
[SPEAKER_07]: Would you borrow more than the Tories?

1033
01:16:28,015 --> 01:16:32,442
[SPEAKER_07]: There are going to be reductions outside the protected departments.

1034
01:16:32,462 --> 01:16:33,624
[SPEAKER_05]: We're going to be reducing spending.

1035
01:16:34,145 --> 01:16:35,828
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, I'm talking about overall spending.

1036
01:16:35,948 --> 01:16:38,231
[SPEAKER_05]: Overall spending would not increase, it would decrease.

1037
01:16:38,392 --> 01:16:40,275
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's likely to fall, yeah.

1038
01:16:40,555 --> 01:16:41,056
[SPEAKER_05]: Likely?

1039
01:16:41,076 --> 01:16:41,196
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

1040
01:16:42,198 --> 01:16:44,020
[SPEAKER_05]: It's a bit of a weasel word, likely, isn't it?

1041
01:16:44,681 --> 01:16:46,364
[SPEAKER_07]: No, I'm setting out the direction of travel.

1042
01:16:46,384 --> 01:16:52,714
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm saying... OK, I'm confused about various of your policies, as is obvious.

1043
01:16:53,285 --> 01:16:54,687
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's take energy policy.

1044
01:16:55,167 --> 01:17:01,255
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, you used to believe that raising energy bills was a great way of helping the environment.

1045
01:17:01,836 --> 01:17:05,040
[SPEAKER_05]: Now you believe in cutting energy bills.

1046
01:17:05,480 --> 01:17:13,791
[SPEAKER_05]: Now you believe that somehow getting people to have a better deal on consumption of oil and gas is better for the environment.

1047
01:17:14,007 --> 01:17:19,138
[SPEAKER_07]: I never said that raising energy bills was a way to solve climate change.

1048
01:17:19,178 --> 01:17:20,000
[SPEAKER_07]: Let me explain.

1049
01:17:20,040 --> 01:17:20,501
[SPEAKER_07]: It was a levy.

1050
01:17:21,223 --> 01:17:22,025
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, let me explain.

1051
01:17:22,646 --> 01:17:31,425
[SPEAKER_07]: Look, I always said, when I was Energy Secretary, that there will be upward pressures on bills as a result of the need to transition to a green economy.

1052
01:17:31,405 --> 01:17:35,449
[SPEAKER_07]: But I also said that we need to make sure the energy market was fair.

1053
01:17:36,050 --> 01:17:39,534
[SPEAKER_07]: And you can't use climate change as an excuse for ripping off the consumer.

1054
01:17:39,874 --> 01:17:41,836
[SPEAKER_07]: And that is what's been happening with the energy companies.

1055
01:17:42,037 --> 01:17:43,979
[SPEAKER_07]: And look, it goes to another big choice at this election.

1056
01:17:44,339 --> 01:17:51,247
[SPEAKER_07]: Who's actually going to stand up to the energy companies and say, we are going to freeze bills until 2017 so prices can only fall.

1057
01:17:51,567 --> 01:17:56,793
[SPEAKER_07]: We are going to give the regulator powers to cut prices so that actually wholesale price reductions get passed on.

1058
01:17:57,314 --> 01:17:59,296
[SPEAKER_07]: Sure, there are upward pressures on bills in the long run.

1059
01:17:59,516 --> 01:18:01,378
[SPEAKER_07]: But that makes it all the more important

1060
01:18:01,358 --> 01:18:03,423
[SPEAKER_07]: that you reform the market to make it fair.

1061
01:18:03,945 --> 01:18:07,273
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you help us with another of your policies, the mansion tax?

1062
01:18:08,537 --> 01:18:15,334
[SPEAKER_05]: According to your leader in Scotland, this is a way of taking money out of the south-east of England and giving it to Scotland.

1063
01:18:15,432 --> 01:18:16,513
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

1064
01:18:16,533 --> 01:18:17,314
[SPEAKER_05]: That is what he said.

1065
01:18:17,394 --> 01:18:17,935
[SPEAKER_05]: No, it isn't.

1066
01:18:17,955 --> 01:18:18,796
[SPEAKER_05]: No, it isn't what he said.

1067
01:18:19,116 --> 01:18:27,486
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, he said specifically there weren't enough properties in Scotland to raise the mansion tax that would fund the Scottish NHS.

1068
01:18:28,067 --> 01:18:32,732
[SPEAKER_05]: It was a way of taking money from the south-east of England and spending it in Scotland.

1069
01:18:32,752 --> 01:18:33,313
[SPEAKER_05]: Shall I explain?

1070
01:18:33,953 --> 01:18:34,674
[SPEAKER_05]: Do, please.

1071
01:18:35,055 --> 01:18:39,600
[SPEAKER_07]: So, we're going to levy a mansion tax on homes above £2 million.

1072
01:18:39,833 --> 01:18:48,686
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, it is true that most of those homes are in the South East, and it's also true that there are consequentials of that spending for Scotland.

1073
01:18:48,706 --> 01:18:50,048
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the way the United Kingdom works.

1074
01:18:50,068 --> 01:18:50,849
[SPEAKER_07]: Consequentials?

1075
01:18:50,869 --> 01:18:55,376
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, it's the way that money gets distributed, and that some of that money will be spent in Scotland.

1076
01:18:55,396 --> 01:18:57,960
[SPEAKER_07]: But let me make this point, because it's really important.

1077
01:18:57,940 --> 01:19:00,383
[SPEAKER_07]: This is part of being a United Kingdom.

1078
01:19:00,904 --> 01:19:09,877
[SPEAKER_07]: If there are young people who are unemployed in Newcastle and the money for a banker's bonus tax, more of it is raised in London, we help those young people in Newcastle.

1079
01:19:10,317 --> 01:19:14,703
[SPEAKER_07]: If another tax falls somewhere else, then we help people across the United Kingdom.

1080
01:19:14,823 --> 01:19:16,886
[SPEAKER_07]: If there are poor kids in London, we help them.

1081
01:19:17,087 --> 01:19:19,149
[SPEAKER_07]: So that is part of being a United Kingdom.

1082
01:19:19,330 --> 01:19:21,593
[SPEAKER_07]: You have redistribution across the United Kingdom.

1083
01:19:21,613 --> 01:19:26,800
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is absolutely a principle of a country that stays together and looks after each other.

1084
01:19:26,780 --> 01:19:34,829
[SPEAKER_05]: What about Alex Salmond's other types of blood money that he would like to exempt or exert from England?

1085
01:19:35,871 --> 01:19:43,379
[SPEAKER_05]: What about, for example, a promise not to recommission Trident, perhaps move it out of Scotland?

1086
01:19:43,419 --> 01:19:44,300
[SPEAKER_05]: Would you go along with that?

1087
01:19:44,741 --> 01:19:44,941
[SPEAKER_07]: No.

1088
01:19:45,181 --> 01:19:45,702
[SPEAKER_05]: No, you wouldn't.

1089
01:19:46,823 --> 01:19:54,272
[SPEAKER_05]: What about starting the high-speed rail line back to front, as it were, in Scotland?

1090
01:19:54,370 --> 01:19:56,934
[SPEAKER_05]: No, look, I'm not going to get into a bargaining game with Alex Salmond.

1091
01:19:56,954 --> 01:19:58,336
[SPEAKER_05]: Look, he's not... You are.

1092
01:19:58,496 --> 01:19:58,937
[SPEAKER_05]: No, I'm not.

1093
01:19:59,638 --> 01:19:59,978
[SPEAKER_07]: You are.

1094
01:19:59,998 --> 01:20:02,361
[SPEAKER_07]: If you have any chance of forming a government, you will, won't you?

1095
01:20:02,542 --> 01:20:03,944
[SPEAKER_07]: No, don't be so presumptuous.

1096
01:20:04,044 --> 01:20:05,085
[SPEAKER_07]: You've got six weeks to go.

1097
01:20:05,105 --> 01:20:06,347
[SPEAKER_07]: You've got six weeks to go.

1098
01:20:06,567 --> 01:20:09,632
[SPEAKER_07]: You don't get to decide the election results six weeks before the general election.

1099
01:20:09,652 --> 01:20:11,635
[SPEAKER_07]: You're important, Jeremy, but not that important.

1100
01:20:11,655 --> 01:20:12,696
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the British people...

1101
01:20:12,716 --> 01:20:13,257
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't want...

1102
01:20:13,237 --> 01:20:14,659
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the British people.

1103
01:20:14,679 --> 01:20:15,780
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't want to decide it.

1104
01:20:15,800 --> 01:20:16,040
[SPEAKER_07]: No, come on.

1105
01:20:16,060 --> 01:20:17,702
[SPEAKER_07]: You know there is no... No, no, no.

1106
01:20:17,722 --> 01:20:18,523
[SPEAKER_05]: You know there is no...

1107
01:20:18,543 --> 01:20:19,344
[SPEAKER_05]: It's the British people.

1108
01:20:19,445 --> 01:20:20,866
[SPEAKER_05]: No, no, let me finish the point.

1109
01:20:21,046 --> 01:20:21,807
[SPEAKER_05]: It's the British people.

1110
01:20:21,827 --> 01:20:24,511
[SPEAKER_05]: You are seriously suggesting you can get an overall majority.

1111
01:20:24,531 --> 01:20:25,692
[SPEAKER_05]: Absolutely right.

1112
01:20:25,772 --> 01:20:26,874
[SPEAKER_07]: Absolutely right.

1113
01:20:28,375 --> 01:20:28,616
[SPEAKER_05]: Right.

1114
01:20:29,316 --> 01:20:32,360
[SPEAKER_05]: In that event, you would be leader of our country.

1115
01:20:34,102 --> 01:20:40,510
[SPEAKER_05]: You know what people say about you because it's hurtful, but you can't be immune to it.

1116
01:20:41,654 --> 01:20:43,969
[SPEAKER_05]: A bloke on the tube said to me last week.

1117
01:20:45,080 --> 01:20:49,986
[SPEAKER_05]: Ed Miliband goes into a room with Vladimir Putin, the door is closed.

1118
01:20:50,086 --> 01:20:56,473
[SPEAKER_05]: Two minutes later, the door is opened again and Vladimir Putin is standing there smiling and Ed Miliband is all over the floor in pieces.

1119
01:20:56,833 --> 01:20:58,295
[SPEAKER_05]: Was that David Cameron who you met on the Tube?

1120
01:20:58,315 --> 01:20:59,036
[SPEAKER_05]: No, it wasn't.

1121
01:20:59,436 --> 01:21:01,218
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't think he uses the Tube very much.

1122
01:21:01,659 --> 01:21:03,081
[SPEAKER_05]: That's rather unfair to him, I think.

1123
01:21:03,141 --> 01:21:03,942
[SPEAKER_05]: It is unfair.

1124
01:21:03,962 --> 01:21:04,282
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

1125
01:21:04,302 --> 01:21:06,645
[SPEAKER_05]: But you understand what the point is here?

1126
01:21:07,005 --> 01:21:09,248
[SPEAKER_05]: The point is people think you're just not tough enough.

1127
01:21:09,408 --> 01:21:11,170
